comment: Shes really nice and great to talk to. However, I felt it was a waste of time and I didnt get much out of it. I felt I didnt learn much about the topic of genocide instead just discussed it. While she is super nice, the lectures were a complete waste of time and the class was poorly set up. Its easy to get a good grade but you may fall asleep.

There were a lot of wasted class days (e.g., 3 classes on student introductions, 4 as extra office hours, etc.). The lectures and readings are repeats of one another--there is also zero primary source material. Professor Bormann is not a tough grader at all and the feedback is minimally helpful. It's an easy course but it's also a quite boring one.
ratingTags: Accessible outside class--Clear grading criteria--So many papers

comment: Amazing professor. You learn a lot from her and she helps you understand the material better than anybody. Extremely accesible, will help you with any questions or concerns and makes you feel comfortable. Lots of papers and a semi tough grader, however her feedback was extremely helpful and she was always extremely fair. All in all a great prof.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Amazing lectures--So many papers

comment: Prof. Boremann is phenomenal. She is a great lecturer and clearly very knowledgeable. Not only that but she is incredibly sweet and always willing to chat and help out her students. In this class the grade consisted of 2 papers, 1 small group presentation and a final project non of which were especially difficult. Very doable and interesting class

A super knowledgable and effective scholar and lecturer. She does at times push her own perspectives almost as facts to her students in class, but that doesn't mean she's close-minded. While she may disagree with you, Professor Bormann encourages and supports her students to have their own points of view.

Here's the thing about Dr. Bormann, if she has a TA you get an easy A, if she is grading the papers herself you will have to work hard for it. Although she is EXTREMELY knowledgeable on Holocaust content, she is very stubborn to allow student points of views and ideas to succeed in papers. Being too politically correct is also her visible weakness.

Prof. Bormann is super nice, and clearly knows a lot about political science, but her Modern Political Thought class was pretty surface. Would not recommend taking if you've taken social & political phil, it's mostly the same authors. If this class is required for you though, you can't go wrong with her.

Professor Bormann is extremely knowledgeable. The thing I like the most is that she understand you take other courses and thus gives you a reasonable amount of papers for you to complete. She is nice and if you work and understand the material you definitely can get an A

Lectures are never boring, her accent and sense of humor make it interesting. Papers are fairly easy, but she can be a kind of tough grader on them. She lets you be creative with the final assignment, so if you're not a big writer there are opportunities to boost your grade.

Great professor, very enthusiastic about the subject and good sense of humor. Class wasn't hard to go to ever. She knows what she's talking about and it doesn't hurt that the class was only 4 1000 word papers
Absolutely fantastic member of the PoliSci department. Love love loved her class.

Class grade  4 papers (each 1000 - 1200 words) worth 20%each of grade and 10% attendanceparticipation. No tests, no surprises, no busy work!  One extra credit (5pt value) assignment.  Great class and professor!
Overall great teacher! Always promotes a positive and engaging learning environment. Her accent is pretty awesome.
She is so great.  She leads an amazing discussion and her accent is fun.  She is very intelligent and really encourages thinking outside of the social norm.  Love her!
Great professor, super helpful, knows what she's teaching. Also, quite funny.
She is a really good professor. She takes time to help, and is always available when you need her. Make sure you hand your work in on time and you will be fine.

The lectures covered most of the important subjects in discrete math and Prof. Jahanjou went over several examples for each problem. The homeworks were challenging but if you do them well you'll be fine for the midterm and final exam. Prof. Jahanjou has a very nice personality and I would definitely take any other courses offered by him.

No grading rubric for any assignments, expect to get points off for random stuff. Reads off of a McGraw-Hill published PowerPoint, don't expect any other resources or examples. Will tell you 'its in the book' for most questions and refer you to the TAs or tutors for anything else.

Dr. Baker is very good at explaining the material and will go over it with you extensively after class or during office hours if you need it. She uses visuals which help and is very organized. She's funny, relies on quizzes and not too many tests, and you should read the textbook but won't fail horribly if you don't. I loved her.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--Participation matters

comment: Dr. Baker is super sweet and helpful. Lectures are interesting and include little demos of topics we're learning. Would definitely recommend

AMAZINF PROF. Shes the sweetest and so helpful and understanding. I wish I couldve taken another one of her classes. I hated stat in high school but it became my favorite class of the semester. Open note tests online.

I love professor Baker! She clearly knows what shes talking about and makes it easy for her students to do well. As long as you take notes and pay attention during the lecture an A is guaranteed. Definitely one of the best psych classes I've taken at Northeastern.
Loved Dr. Baker- so clear and helpful, easily accessible for feedback, and one of the best psych professors I've had at NU.

This class was pretty tough, there was a fair amount of outside work involved. However, Dr. Baker is one of my favorite professors at Northeastern making it more than worth it. Although the class can be difficult, Dr. Baker always makes time for her students when they are struggling and really wants her students to succeed!
show up and understand what she's lecturing, then before the exam just review the slides and you should be ok

She really tries her best to make sure you understand the material. Personally I would have liked to see more interactive activities in the class, however, she is a fair grader and even takes her own exams to make sure.

Posts all slides online, so don't have to go. She is super interesting and she tries to make the class fun. So happy I took it with her. The writing assignments and tests were easy as hell. Great for an Area B Psych course. Never used the textbook and go an average of 99 in the class. If you know the review sheet you are fine for test.

She's awesome. Cognition was one of the easiest classes I have ever taken (not in a bad way at all). She just makes it easy to learn and easy to do well on tests. I didn't buy the textbook and had no trouble studying for exams. Occasional homework takes about half an hour every few weeks. Great class.

Overall, Dr. Baker is a good professor who teaches Cognition decently. The course is student friendly in terms of grades and extra credit, and beneficial for learning. However, I dislike how she posts her slides onto BB last minute and how she sets aside class time for homework sharing time, which feels like elementary school show and tell time.

LOVE LOVE LOVE prof. baker! she's super helpful and knowledgeable. she is clear and always willing to explain concepts. her tests are very straight-forward, and all of the information is covered in class, or at least, in the textbook. the only homework is a few short writing assignments, which are easy

Professor Baker is a great teacher. She posts the power points from class and sends you review slides before the tests. If you know the review slides, you'll do well on the test. She's really helpful and willing to meet/answer any questions you have. Overall, easy to do well and interesting class

I had her for cognition and its the best psych elective I've yet taken, thanks to her.  Its an awesome subject to begin with, but she makes it even more fun.  Her tests are a joke too, which is awesome.

I had her for cognition, the class is pretty easy and if you have taken Fundamentals of Psychology, there is a lot of overlap in material.  There are only 3 tests with lots of extra credit on them (it's possible to get a 115% on a test).  There is no midterm or final and no homework.  Should be an easy A unless your stupid like me and pulled a B+.
He made basic Spanish impossible.

Profe is great. I've taken two classes with him and he obviously is very passionate about the material he teaches. He genuinely wants his students to succeed and so he will hold any conversation in Spanish so his students can practice. It is extremely helpful.
Literally loved Professor Yelin. Very good teacher and he makes class entertaining. Participation is VERY important. If you want a class that will teach you spanish skills take this one.

Profe Yelin is awesome! He structures the class as mostly group work and discussion- which really forces you to be engaged and learn. He's very accessible outside of class and responds to emails super quick. You just need to come in being ready to put in work. Overall he really cares about his students.

I thought of dropping this course many times in the first few weeks. The homework was very hard and the software we used was a pain. HOWEVER, give the man the credit because he gave a reasonably long time length to submit your assignments. The exams were not hard. He loved it when you engage which really helped your grades and the lectures.
ratingTags: Respected--Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: His lectures were very clear and overall useful, but if you aren't actually interested in topics you'll be bored. Homework was pain mainly because the textbooks not on chegg. Tests were really fair though and if you studied they're no problem. Graders gave partial credit which was a huge for engineering. Overall really nice guy.

Do not take this class with Andrew. He is incredibly dull in his lectures, uses his colleague's mediocre, typo-ridden textbook (which in itself is very unprofessional), and fails to effectively communicate key course ideas. On top of this he assigns extremely long and difficult homework. I would not recommend taking his class.
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Tough grader

comment: First and foremost, i regret taking this course with Andrew. His lectures are extremely dull and lengthy. Writes so  much on the board, most of which is theories and derivations that you will never return to when studying for test/exam. His homeworks are the worst, by far. The software he expects us to use is Mastan2. This software is horrendous.

Homework takes forever and is very hard and kind of useless. Lectures are too conceptual and he hardly gives any example questions. He writes a lot of notes but does not take the time to explain for students to fully understand. Erases what he writes on the board too quickly. Worst design class to take.
one of the best teachers ive had at school. His class was always interesting and his lectures were very well done. Hard homework but thats to be expected for steel design.

Professor Myers has literally changed my entire world view of engineering.  OMG!!!1!  I can't even look at a bridge anymore without thinking about him.  HE IS SO CUTE.  He likes the Red Sox.  I like the Red Sox.  He likes math. I like math.  I feel like he's sorta perfect.  Take his class.  Just don't take it with your boyfriend.
Professor Myers makes me love Structural Analysis.

I love Professor Apfeld so much!! He really cares about his students and takes your feedback on the class into serious consideration. He always emphasizes going to office hours and he really tries hard to make sure students are doing well. He makes the classroom a safe and inclusive place--overall a very kind man and great professor

Personality wise professor apfeld is so understanding and actually cares about your mental health Quizzes and Tophat questions were easy Exams were somewhat confusing but fair- please do the practice exams Hes open to any questions in office hours but doesnt really answer them well during lectures Mediocre lecturer, reads off slides a lot

Dr. Apfeld doesn't really go too in depth with the material, and usually reads off of powerpoint slides. Not too helpful when in need of some clarification for some material. Generally a nice man, but does not make things clear enough for his students.

Professor Apfeld is a PowerPoint reader. He gives HW from the textbook and doesnt know how to answer them. His test questions are weirdly worded. He loves to talk about worms, but they get extremely annoying. His office hours are useless, get ready to self teach yourself. Only good thing about the class was that the man is nice and the cat memes.
Just a ppt reader, boring.
Loves talking about his c. elegans. Sweet, funny guy but unfortunately a terrible professor. Class was based on tophats, three exams, and a final :/
Loves talking about model organisms
good!

I think the way she organized the class online was very unique. I enjoyed it a lot more because a friend and I took the class together so we were able to watch the assigned movies together. Readings are interesting but painfully long. Good news is she's a pretty easy grader. Also a lot of assignments are through Twitter for some reason.

Professor Goodwin knows her stuff and she's hilarious, but her insecurity to be the smartest person in the room creates a very toxic classroom. She looks like a cool, progressive prof on Twitter, but the entire class is confused and frustrated literally all the time (hot take: pictures all over the syllabus is NOT helpful at all).

Engaging professor, clear she cares about religious studies. Lectures are the same information from readings. She isn't great at providing detailed feedback and struggles with providing resources (e.g. assignment sheets) in a timely manner. She grades classic humanities style (i.e. meeting all requirements is a B, you must do more to get an A.)

Professor Goodwin is clearly very passionate and it was reflected in the course. That said, she is not great at giving extensive feedback (she does give feedback but it is brief and not given in a particularly timely manner). Your course grade also is significantly impacted by several group projects so it is not entirely within your own control.
Shes a decent professor but is very strict with grading. If youre looking for an easy A to fill an elective this is not a good course to take

Very enthusiastic about the material. She puts a lot of time into making sure people feel included and that her students get the topics. I came in with 0 knowledge and a closed mind about religion, but left with a broad knowledge of the religions of the world and respect religion a lot more. One of the best teachers I have had.

Weekly quizzes that are a breeze if you pay attention in class and do the homework. A few major tests, but he always sends out practice tests. Very accessible outside of class and overall an amazing lecturer who really cares for his students' success.

Has to be one of the clearest lecturers Ive had. Didnt look at the textbook once, only ever rewatched lecture at 2x speed and still absorbed everything. Gives weekly quizzes, but as long as you just watch the damn lectures and copy the notes, you will do well. He does so many practise qs in class, its great!

Prasanth is super funny and an amazing lecturer. Diff Eq sounds like a daunting class at first but he makes it really easy to understand. You don't even really have to do the homework to pass, just pay attention in the lectures, especially when he does examples. Ample amounts of time for quizzes/tests, and the problems are very reasonable.

Professor George is a fantastic teacher. He can take complex concepts and break them down into small, consumable ideas. He makes it clear what is necessary for the course and what to expect. He is also a funny guy that is good at making math lectures as interesting as possible.

Prasanth George is my biological father. An absolutely wonderful dude. His lectures were very clear and even though I never did the homework, I was still able to keep on top of the material and do well. Really great professor-his lectures are organized with clear examples.
Really great professor-his lectures are organized with clear examples. If you attend lecture, there are no surprises on the quizzes. Truly, one of the best professors I've had so far.
One of the best professors I've had - really puts in effort and the organization to make his lectures well worth attending

Prasanth George is one of the best math professors I've have. He is very kind and his lectures are interesting. He explains everything clearly and makes excellent notes. He gives example problems that are super great for preparing for weekly quizzes and the exams. If you have the chance to take his math class, I highly recommend it.

Professor George Is amazing. By far the best professor I've had at NU. His lectures aren't boring, gives great examples, and helps his students. His examples are exactly what you would see on the tests and quizzes.

Professor George has been by far the best teacher I have had at Northeastern. He is funny, a great lecturer, and you learn a lot. He makes it very clear what will be on quizzes and exams so there's never any surprises. I took his Diffeq and linear algebra class for engineering. Overall, good guy, good class, and its pretty easy to get an A.
Extremely good lecturer, extremely easy to follow. Can be snarky if you're late or skip class, but is otherwise one of the best professors at Northeastern
ratingTags: Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures

comment: One of the best professors I've had - really puts in effort and the organization to make his lectures well worth attending
Best professor I've had at Northeastern so far.
He wrote YIKES! on my exam. I was trying my best and didn't do that bad. Don't take his class. Very rude.
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Tough grader

comment: One the best professors I have had in a long time. His lectures are clear and he gives an adequate amount of relevant examples plus very helpful notes.
He was good.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures--Clear grading criteria

comment: Professor George was a great instructor. I had him for Calculus 2 last summer and I cannot stress how great he was hence I took Differential equations and linear algebra with him again. He goes through each problem very thoroughly, answers every student's question very thoroughly and cracks a joke every now and then.

GoAT. I was considering changing my major before taking calc2 with him during the summer. I look forward to going to his classes and office hours. He's very helpful. Also very funny and knows how to get your attention if he feels that you've tuned out. Cool guy

One of the best math professors I've had at Northeastern. Lectures are slow and easy to follow. You need to put in effort and should do the homework and show up to lecture if you want to be successful, but neither homework nor attendance is mandatory. He's a little soft-spoken, but listen to him if you can because he's actually hilarious. OG homie

One of the best professors I've ever had. So good I willingly took an 8am just to have his class. I've had Professor George for Calc 2 and Calc 3. He's so good at explaining concepts simply and clearly. His handwriting is fantastic and goes at a reasonable pace. He is very lenient and tests are quite easy if you pay attention and copy the notes.

He is by far the best professor I have ever had. I would give him the maximum praises if I could. His lectures are very clear, and well organized. He creates an easy environment to ask questions in, and he is extremely kind. He makes the material as manageable as possible, and always is happy when coming to class.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: Prasanth is the MAN! He's hilarious and snarky, and more importantly a fantastic calc teacher. He makes it very clear what you need to do and does lots of examples, as well as takes class input; quizzes are easy if you put in the work. He's really nice in office hours and makes it seem like he wants you to pass. One of the best calc profs!
ratingTags: Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: He is the best professor at NEU, and I would recommend him to anyone. I  had a hard time in Calc 2 and was worried about taking Calc 3, however, he is extremely clear in his teaching. I understood everything perfectly, and for that reason, he is by far the best professor for this course, or any course he teaches.

Prasanth is one of the best math teachers I have ever had, and my favorite professor I have had so far here at NEU. He is extremely clear, has great handwriting, and has the best subtle sense of humor. If you want to do well in his class, he makes it easy for you to do so. He is incredibly reasonable about grades. Take his class!

Prasanth is literally one of the best math professors I've ever had and is basically Brown Jesus. During class, he explains concepts incredibly clearly, gives plenty of notes, works through example problems, and outlines what problems you're expected to know how to do on tests and quizzes. Show up, pay attention, and you'll do fine in Calc 2.
One of the best math teachers I've had. He breaks everything down so well and everything is extremely clear. As long as you show up to lecture and pay attention it's an easy A.
Had him for calculus 2, such a good teacher that I have to get him for calc 3 as well. Best math teacher I have ever had.
He was great. The final was hard for most of us and he practically saved our lives.
Proof based class. Very hard at the beginning but you will learn a lot.

Prof. George is a great professor! I had him for Calculus 3, and he really knows how to explain the material well. He is kind, and he openly encourages you to attend his office hours, which I recommend. He gives weekly quizzes, but they aren't critical for your grade. The material is tough, so go to class and study, and you'll have a good semester.

George was a pretty good calc 3 professor, but if you're questioning whether or not you should be in calc 3, you probably shouldn't be in calc 3. My advice would be to only take the course if 100% necessary because even though I took calc 1 and 2 in high school, it was by far the hardest math class I've ever taken.

Professor George is very clear and concise during his lectures. He also has great handwriting and explains the material in a way that is very comprehensible. His lectures were enjoyable to sit through purely because the content was taught very effectively. Quizzes every Thursday with only 2-3, very straightforward problems. 3 exams including final.
He was the best! And he really cares about his students' success. I would definitely recommend taking class with him!

definitely one of the best professors at NEU. If you can take a class with him, I HIGHLY recommend it, very clear and helpful, just overall an amazing teacher. Also extremely respectful and approachable.
The best MATH prof I've ever had!!!
This is the god professor

Professor Spilecki is a very nice person. She will grant you an extension for pretty much anything and is very understanding. You end up writing a paper every couple weeks, and they are usually a bit lengthy. Her grading gets easier as the semester progresses, even if you do not improve. Not super hard, but also not a super easy A.
Had her for first year writing, she made it very interesting and enjoyable. Grading and workload is fair but not super easy. Would take again.

Really cool and passionate. Her essay topics are more interesting than a lot of other professors and I really enjoyed listening to her talk. She gets to know her students and there isn't a lot of reading. She even nominated one of my essays to be published in a journal.
Difficult to understand what is required from class. Nice lady and means well however i don't believe that she conveys information clearly.

Prof Spilecki is the best! My interest in writing increased immensely over the semester because of the interesting writing topics and essays. My own writing definitely improved. Not too much work and pretty easy class

Professor Spilecki made College Writing an interesting experience. She's very acoomodating, and doesn't every really get upset with the class. The workload is very light for a college writing class, and the workshops are very helpful. As long as you show up and write all the papers on the day they're do, you'll do fine in this class.

The class (Econ of Sports) was enjoyable. I find that Prof. Konan is a nice guy, offering helpful review sessions and makeup exams. However, he does make you buy Top Hat, he goes over time in most classes, and he is poor at responding to emails. Overall he is a decent choice if you like the class being taught. Be sure to do notes on the textbook.

Professor Konan is the worst professor I have ever had. His lecture notes are confusing and if you ask him questions he gets frustrated. He ignored both "care days" we had this semester and held class even though he was reminded of them by students. He is a harsh grader and very boring lecturer. Avoid him as a professor if you can.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Test heavy--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: He started the semester with a bit of a harsh tone, but he warms up to students and enjoys participation. He is not a very fast responder to emails or when grading assignments, but he definitely is passionate about the subject, and the class can be interesting. I recommend reading the textbook before or after class so you can soak the info in well.
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: Please please please do yourself a favor and do not take this professor. Yes he cares, and is not a bad guy. But his class interaction, his teaching style, and overall effectiveness is awful. At the start of the semester, questions were discouraged and if you do he's stubborn.
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Accessible outside class--Get ready to read

comment: He was okay, he seems like he cares but can be difficult to speak to. Which seems like it wouldn't be a huge deal, but he wouldn't speak about them in class. They were random and unrelated to the bigger picture of what we were learning. Even if you do really well on the math portion, you won't do well on exams or class b/c of weird multiple choice
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: Prof Konan's lectures are a mess. He is disorganized and gets lost and goes on tangents easily and often. He tries to teach and cover upper level econ theory in a couple weeks when the class has no prereqs. Unless you have a solid micro and macro theory background you will be lost. He grades based on how much he likes students and is way too harsh

Prof. H. is a reasonable and approachable guy who welcomes questions from students. The class and homework are similar to the textbook. I found it hard to follow his lecture sometimes but overall he is passionate about the course. He likes the economist Krugman, for reference.
ratingTags: Respected--Accessible outside class--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: I took macro theory with him and it was okay. His lectures are very slideshow heavy and the only way I understood the class was from re reading my notes and reading the textbook. As long as you do practice problems from the book, his tests are fine. He is very smart, but he doenst explain the material thoroughly.

I really like Prof. Lindhe! He is reasonable/accommodating, personable, and very available outside class. He seemed passionate about the subject and gave fair assignments/tests. One thing I loved was that he offered materials from previous semesters to do as practice for the quizzes/tests! He is a good choice for probably any course

Lindhe is a great math professor. He makes things clear and if you do the hw you will be fine. Practice material for tests and quizzes is exactly like the actual thing. Drops a quiz and overall class isn't too hard but depends on how much u put into it. Overall super nice guy and great teacher.

Professor Lindhe was most definitely one of the best math teachers I have ever had. He explained all the material really well and went over everything he would test so there were no surprises on exams or quizzes. He also provided us with a lot of extra material, in case we were confused about any particular subject matter. I highly recommend him.

Lindhe was one of, if not the best professor I've had. He connects very well with students (even in online class format) and is passionate about the material. He explained calc3 very well and I and my friends never felt lost. He hosted live lectures and addressed any and every question or concern. The class was graded on 4 quizzes and 3 tests.
I love him and I take his class this semester again.

Always prepared for lecture + engaging. We have a quiz every week and he drops the two lowest grades - great way to make sure you're keeping up. Homework is suggested for each section but not mandatory/graded. Very willing to help outside class. Gives partial credit. Doesn't really teach a deep understanding - more like "plug and chug"
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Clear grading criteria--Amazing lectures

comment: Dr Lindhe is a helpful and supportive instructor. He is always ready to support you outside of class. But sometimes in lecture I struggle understanding why certain equations work. He seems to focus on take all the theorems and plug in numbers rather than learning why and problem solving skills. Overall, it was a great class as hes always prepared.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: In past semesters this professor prepared his students for finals and test. However, this semester we really got blindsided by the final (which is 40% of your grade). The final had problem unlike anything we had done the whole semester and nothing like the past exams. He told us to study past exams and we'd be fine but that was clearly not the case

He grades by 2 quizzes, 2 takehomes, and 2 tests. All of these were easy and really similar to the ones from previous years. The final (40%) was impossible, with problems that were much more harder than the ones we had done in class. I found his way of teaching the class boring and the explanations weren't clear for me, he just did problems.
Love this man. Makes the material straightforward and easy to learn. Gives plenty of examples and is always willing to answer questions.

Prof. Lindhe is a fantastic professor. His lectures were very clear, easy to follow, and explained new concepts in the best way possible. He loves what he does, and that shows when he is teaching. He made himself accessible to students, and was understanding when issues come up. I found the class to be very easy because he had us well prepared

The nicest math teacher I have ever had. Gives a lot of partial credit. In general a fair grader, knowledgeable, nice, helpful, passionate about math. The class though was not very challenging (the department's fault, not his) and the examples shown in class lacked variety and didn't promote deeper understanding of the concept.
He is mean for every test or quiz grades. He never round up grade and is hard to communicate with. All grades are non-negotiable. I won't take his class again.

Prof. Lindhe is an incredibly talented professor that really wants you to succeed. He provides so many resources and really explains the material. He uses class time efficiently and no matter the time of day, he always has a smile on his face, ready to help. A wonderful human, a wonderful course. Would highly recommend.
I would defiantly take his classes again. He is a REALLY good professor!!!!!
Wonderful teacher. The class isn't stressful at all, but you learn everything you have to know.

Really good lecture and he is willing to answer questions in class. 2 take-home and 2 in class quizzes. The take-homes are a little bit harder, and he will give help if you asked. Offering reviews for tests and quizzes which are helpful. If you study hard and understand the materials, easy to get A.

Prof Lindhe is great! He's super clear and really wants his students to do well. He gives review sheets before each test that are really similar to the test. He's a really fair grader and gives a lot of partial credit. Always willing to answer questions. Wish I took him for MATH3081.
Clear, good professor.
Best Calc professor I ever had! Do the practice quizzes before the quiz and you'll do great. Super friendly and explains concepts very clearly. Really patient.
Great prof.

This is the second time I have had Professor Lindhe. He is the man! Both times I have had him he has taught the material well. He is very good with explaining topics and will help during office hours if you show up. His testquiz reviews  are also great indicators as to what type of problems are going  to be asked of you.

Clearly puts very little effort into teaching or even understanding the material he is teaching to the class.  Offers no understanding of the material, and most of the class time is spent doing slight variations of the same problems over and over again.  Tests are all just plugging numbers into formulas, anyone with a formula sheet could ace them.

One of the best math professors at the school. You'll know exactly what to expect coming into every class, and you'll know exactly what to expect on the tests/quizzes. Pay attention, take notes, ask questions, and you'll learn a lot

if you take good notes, you are likely to pass. He gives clear explanations and loves when people comes to him with questions. I never used the textbook but I'm still doing great in the class. He tries his hardest to pass everyone.

Usually good at teaching and explaining.  Occasionally unclear, but he does a good job with examples, which makes up for it.  Will never surprise you on a test with stuff you haven't already seen.  Pretty non-strict during class, too.

He spends a lot of time on examples in class, which helps with learning a lot more than the way most math professors spend the entire time dissecting theory. The way he explains things can be a little muddled sometimes, but when he goes over the examples it clears everything up.

You do not have to do the homework or read the textbook at all. But if you don't make sure you pay complete attention in class and take EVERY note, as his lectures are very helpful. Tests and quizzes are relevant to teachings. Sometimes does a poor job of fully explaining concepts. Final is deceptively easy..didn't do as well as I thought, wtf?

HATED that class and him. He speaks and goes way too fast and has a deep hatred of foreigners. Also a harsh grader and is useless in his office hours. I understood things WAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAY better with a tutor than with him. He sucks.

Love her! Would never make it through this course without her support and constant encouragement! One of my hardest classes for sure, but she makes it fun and interesting.
great teacher.  should have been an easy A but only myself to blame.
Best professor at Northeastern. Sign up early though - her classes fill up right away!
CHOOSE HER. One of the best professors I ever had at Northeastern!
AMAZING professor! She knew us all by name, made us laugh, and took the time to explain everything so that it all made sense. If you can get into her class, jump at it!

A decent professor who cares about her students. Her tests are HARD, but homework and participation help weigh the grade. She is helpful,but can be a little misleading when it comes to her tests. Do I recommend her? I would say yes if you keep up with your homework, participate, and do well on two of the four tests she gives.

Funny, nice, really cares about her students. Lots of class participation. I was NOT looking forward to taking stats but actually enjoy her class and I have learned a lot.  She makes really complex topics simple and we laugh a lot.
Awesome! The best professor at Northeastern!

Fun person who teaches Stats from the ground up. Extremely helpful if you feel "iffy" about the course. Easy, straightforward exams with a lot of opportunity to increase your grade over the course of the semester with homeworks. Highly recommended

Professor Money is a great professor, she provides clear learning materials and all information on her tests and quizzes is related to the readings and lectures. Very kind and understanding with accommodations as well.

Money's lectures do not cover what's on the exam, but her tests and quizzes are open book. There are weekly discussion questions that raise your grade and count as participation. Overall, this class is an easy A, but you won't learn much.

Psych and the Law covered interesting topics, but I wasnt a big fan at all of Dr. Money. Overall, a pretty boring class. She puts very little effort into her teaching. Ridiculously easy A. Everything is open-book. I honestly learned very little despite my A in the class.

Best professor ever! Very clear lectures, very good at explaining concepts. Always had a positive attitude. Always willing to answer questions in/out of class. Very approachable, based mainly on discussion boards and two exams and two quizzes, I highly recommend taking her classes!!! Literally, everyone I talked to in the class loved her

Pr Money will probably be one of the best professors I'll ever have. She cares more about our learning than sticking to her syllabus (e.g. she removed an entire unit from one of our midterms because she didn't think we had gone over it in-depth enough in lecture)

This class was easy because Prof Money posts her notes, is SO energetic (ie, you won't fall asleep in class!), and gives you study guides that outline exactly what will be on the exam. There is a lot of material, she even allows textbooks. A fascinating course, I think all psychology majors should take this! Karina is one of the best at NU!

This is what a tenured professor should be like. She's very energetic about what she teaches. She presents a lot of material, but it's bearable since there are little breaks between her lectures that test for comprehension. Highly recommended!

Dr. Money is the greatest professor that I have ever had. Her class was extremely interesting, she was always there to help and took the time to make sure that the material was understood. Learned so much in her class, I wish all professors were like her.
Pr. Money is a wonderful professor, she's a great teacher and extremely sweet outside of class. Do the study guides thoroughly and you will do well on the exams.

Dr. Money exceeds expectations in every area. She is brilliant and willing to help and, most importantly, pause for student understanding and discussion. Lectures are engaging and informative. Her honesty about topics in psychology and human nature is reassuring and inspirational. She is genuinely an amazing human.

Professor Money is really straightforward and gives a lot of opportunities for extra credit. There are two exams and two quizzed and you are allowed to use textbooks and powerpoints for each exam/quiz.

Karina is the best psychology professor, she gives so much opportunity for extra credit and whenever she's done with lecture for the week she dismisses the class. Cannot recommend enough how much she's a real homie
Took psyc and law with doctor Money just to get an intro to the area. The course was so good that now I'm considering law school. Highly recommend!

Everyone is being rather harsh about her teaching during COVID. I believe that although it is true that her online lectures are a struggle as she isn't technologically sound, she offers the class time to work together and truly cares about the class. Always willing to move discussions.
A typical intro course was made really fun and manageable. The case study at the end was fantastic, really saw what we worked the semester for

Psyc & Law is a really easy class to get an A, but don't expect to actually learn anything. Professor Money just reads exactly from the slides, and sometimes she doesn't even know what she's reading. The final exam was straight off the Internet; she didn't even come up with exam questions herself. As I said, easy A but I learned nothing.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Test heavy--Lecture heavy

comment: If you are interested in the material and want to learn something, don't take a class with her. If you want an easy A, then she's your prof. Reads off the slides from the textbook, adds nothing to the class. You don't even need to have the sound on to do well. As a friend said, "If all of our classes were like this our degrees would mean nothing."
Standard intro type course. Lectures are all you get (with some participation). Reads directly from her slides. Didn't learn a lot. Pretty boring tbh.
Lecture heavy and a lot to read, but worth it
Great prof, interesting subject. You put in a little effort youll get an A
Professor Money makes you fall in love with the subject and inspires to explore psychology in your own time. Everts we covered can be related to real life and this is amazing!

Dr. Money makes everything easy going and fun, and does her best to bring in-person experience to online classes. Her grading criteria is very easy to follow and the overall experience is magnificent.
Engaging and fun even through zoom! highly recommend such a great class!
ratingTags: Accessible outside class--Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: I loved this class so much it was about personality I learned so much about all the different personality types it was really interesting. I loved the lectures they were fun and informative I would highly recommend her!!
ratingTags: Accessible outside class--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment: amazing class! cannot say enough about this class. Not only was it interesting, I learned a lot and look forward to taking more!! highly recommend!!

She was nice, and the class was such an easy A, but I actually don't recommend her. It was not an enjoyable class. She simply reads off her ppt slides and exams are a joke. I feel like I learned nothing. I might as well have taken it in high school.
I found her lectures to not be that helpful. As long as you read the textbook you'll get a good grade
Take her for an A
Great class! Psych and law was awesome fun I learned a lot from the lectures and book to the case study project where you conduct research. Overall great class would highly recommend her!
ratingTags: Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures

comment: Great class! It was for foundations in psych she is hilarious, gives great informative lectures and as long as you show up to class participate you'll be fine. Do the work and READ you'll pass. Highly recommend her!
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Group projects--Amazing lectures

comment: had money for PSYC1208 and foundations. really easy but she just reads off the slides. have some nice class discussions that are interesting. tests are annoying but not hard. she really didn't put any effort in once classes went online, no lectures and just class discussions. great for an A but not if you really want to remember everything

does not teach. at all. reads through the powerpoints but will not post them on canvas because theres others that are already on there, however those are not nearly as detailed (20 sides vs. 120 slides). runs through 2 chapters per 1.5 hour class and does not explain anything, again, just reads the powerpoint. tests contradict the book. cant learn

The lectures for this class were great, and I always looked forward to going to class. Money is hilarious. The tests were based on material discussed in class and material in the textbook. Make sure to show up to class bc Money will give you a list of everything that will be on a test.

Currently taking her Personality course, which has been one of my favorite courses so far! She gives funny relevant lectures, which if you are not reading will never understand!- So READ! If you want to have a clue what she is talking about when she asks you to apply concepts to analyze a case study in groups- READ the text it is that simple!
ratingTags: Amazing lectures--Participation matters--Get ready to read

comment: Law is amazing! you learn so much through the lectures and the text. Open book tests what could be bettter? She is amazing and available outside of class can't say that a lot of professors are willing to do that because they want to. Show up, do the work and you will get what you put in out of it! Would highly recommend taking ANY of her classes!
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--Amazing lectures

comment: Child Development was honestly my favorite of two classes at NU! Her lectures are funny and insightful you learn so much. It is wise to read the course book because it will give more information to add to the lectures in class so you know what is going on. Partciapte in class discussions, ask questions you will get more out of it!

She pulls questions from the old textbook (that we don't have) so she insists that we've covered the material on the tests but it's almost always impossible to find the answers in the textbook since she doesn't use the new one to make her tests. She also always shows up late to class and fussed at us for wanting the ppts before the exam.

Dr. Money is a great person but a terrible professor. It is obvious that she spent very little time and energy on this class. She was consistently 10-20 minutes late but made us wait for her. Her exams do not represent what she teaches at all, he only reason you can get 100 on the tests are because they are straight from the internet.

Literally reads off her powerpoint. A little unorganized. Will legit go over the exam questions the day prior. Boring class, but interesting topics sometimes. Doesn't give good feedback on the final paper.

Very lecture heavy and lectures very quickly but exams are open notes/open textbook and she usually sends the PowerPoints before exams. Exams are very straightforward and she reviews exactly what topics will be on the exam before. If you put in the effort to take notes well and participate in class then its nearly impossible not to get an A.
ratingTags: Participation matters--Graded by few things--Clear grading criteria

comment: Easiest class ever. We never had any homework nor did we have to read the book to do well. Don't bother buying it, really. Professor Money is very funny and relatable and brings her super cute daughter in sometimes. There are 3 tests, all open book and open internet, as well as being take home online. AND the final isnt cumulative! Its hard to fail
Dr. Money is an awesome and easy teacher. Her lectures are so fun and engaging. Her tests are all open textbook so it's pretty much impossible to not get an A.

Dr. Money should be your first choice if you are NOT a psyc major. You will not learn much but will receive an A. Tests are 75 % and participation is 25 %. All tests are open textbook and you can have a cheat sheet too. All of her lectures are relaxed and discussion based. Class was often canceled or dismissed early. Easy A but I didnt learn much.

Best professor I've had so far. She cares about her students individually with classes of over 50 kids and she really tries to change things up in terms of learning styles. Her tests always come from in class material and she takes her time teaching instead of rushing with the syllabus. 100% recommend. Do yourself a favor and take her class.

Dr. Money was my favorite teacher that I had this semester and I really hope I have her again. All 3 of her tests were open note and she basically tells you all of the questions during review. Her lectures are very thorough and she is overall a great person. There are not many other assignments besides the test, maybe three, so make sure to do well

This was honestly my favorite class, Dr. Money kept things fun and moving. Though attendance is not technically mandatory I still recommend you go, the information you learn is well worth going to class! I highly recommend this class!

I loved this class so much! While not technically mandatory attendance, she notices who shows up and participates and it helps you a lot. If you pay attention and contribute, you're golden. It's not difficult content, and the discussions were honestly really fun and interesting. Great class if you're a fan of true crime. Highly recommend.

Dr. Money is a really smart, passionate, and laid back professor. Emphasis on laidback. Her lectures are stress-free and super chill. Great professor and knows a lot about Psychology and has a lot of crazy cool stories. She can sometimes be a little too laid-back, but I'd still take her class again.
ratingTags: Clear grading criteria--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: If you want an easy A with a general understanding of the material, this is for you. If you actually want to learn things you haven't before, not for you. Also really white washed class. Talked to other people who took the same class and they had such great experiences that I wish I didn't take this class with her. Disappointing all around
My favorite professor at Northeastern. Class is super easy and she is so funny and easy going. If you are taking Foundations of Psychology, definitely take it with Dr. Money.
The best professor I could ever ask. She is caring, knowledgeable and knows how to teach. I love Psychology because of her inspiration.

Developmental Psyc Course: One group paper, presentation for extra 10 pt credit optional; Open book and open note. Take during Summer 1. Super cool and chill class environment. Was always understanding and energetic. Definitely would take another course with her again.

This was a hard class, challenging but it was very rewarding. Many quizzes, mid-term, and final. There is also the opportunity for extra credit along the way. The professor was very fair and accessible. There is a lot to learn in this class so be prepared to put in the work each week. If you put in the work, you will do well.
He is really good professor. I have learn a lot of useful CS useful knowledge from his class. Definitly recommend to take his class.
Clear in explaining ideas,patient with all students and being fun with answering questions. Would definitely take his class again if I have a chance.

Drew is absolutely a gem and amazing in Algorithms! He does not assume that students know the pre-requisites and covers every topic right from the foundation and gradually advances the level. Graphs are the best! Assignments are well designed to cover lecture concepts, med to high difficulty. Definitely recommend him! You won't regret :)

Least intimidating professor I've taken so far. Very humble, down to earth. Very accomodating to confused students, and was extremely accessible throughout the course. Homework grading was slow but he released solutions asap, so that didn't matter. Lenient, lots of extra credit, yet still learned a lot from in. Would take again.
ratingTags: Accessible outside class--Clear grading criteria--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: Humble, relatable fellow. He gives precrastinators a chance to stay ahead (ha) in the class schedule by releasing lectures the day before. Very open to incredibly stupid questions (a lot of which asked by me). Slow grading, makes it difficult to fix up approaches to homework. Also hardly available on Friday/weekends (at least for summer).
Did a great job teaching the course in the pandemic. Always reachable on piazza and outside. Makes regrading interesting by introducing challenges.
ratingTags: Accessible outside class--Clear grading criteria--Lecture heavy

comment: He takes things seriously, but is also ridiculously in touch with college aged students (probably has something to do with his age, but he's also generally a cool guy). Took a tough situation with a hard class (COVID semester) and made the material accessible nonetheless. I would recommend.
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Accessible outside class--Test heavy

comment: There are lots of group projects which takes away from flexibility and impacts grades. Feedback from professor not efficient and inconsistent. Tough grading and 100% is very rare. Professor does not grade in a timely manner nor posted additional materials in a timely manner.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Group projects--Tough grader

comment: Very tough grader with very limited productive feedback, if any. Would answer every question with a question with no clear answer. Too many group projects which made it difficult to do well. Spotaneous last minute classes each week. Did not post any additional learning material and when she did it was the following week.
Good teacher but too many presentation assignment.

She is kind, patient and always with a smile. She arranges the agenda in a reasonable way that you do not have to write thirty pages paper in one night, only if you are right to the point. There are lots of fun activities in her class, you will get to work together with your classmates to feel teamwork. She brings Bagles for late-night classes.

Overall good at teaching the material. Acct is hard for most students, including me, and you have to pay attention & do the hw to understand it. Lectures can be boring sometimes, but she has fill in the blank notes to keep you on track. Quizzes usually every 2 weeks, 2 midterms, & 1 cumulative final. Honestly, if you put the time in, you'll be fine

Professor Summer is good at trying her best to ensure students succeed, but this isn't really the case. To be frank, its hard to understand her during her lectures and they are all very boring. Her slides and handouts are somewhat useful however, but I would just look at them on your own... Be prepared to teach yourself.

Good person but very disorganized and confusing when lecturing. Never has proper due dates and often forgets student Qs, assignment dates, or her own announcements. Discussion Qs every week, couple of group projects, and 1 midterm and 1 final both just answering 1 question. Interesting course, easy because she makes it, but try for another prof

She is a really nice person but is all over the place. You can get through the course without reading the book if you understand the course concepts easily. The class has 2 projects that are worth almost half of your grade and participation is worth 30%. It was her first time teaching this class and I think it is going to get harder in the future.
ratingTags: Accessible outside class--Participation matters--Graded by few things

comment: Lots of material to learn. Usually very boring powerpoints she goes over that you can just look at later, so I skipped half the classes. Honestly a bit hard to understand her and grasp the material. 5-6 quizzes, 1 midterm, 1 final noncumulative. A 100+ student class so no real connection to her, but I would take again; that's just the nature of it

Professor is obviously passionate about the material, but struggles to clearly explain it. The slides are basically useless; all of the material on the exams are what she lectures on. It doesn't help that she moves through the material extremely quickly. 75% of the grade is from three exams, so there is not much room to get your grade up.

Dr. Libro's class was very lecture heavy and your grade depends on a few tests and quizzes. If you are self-motivated and pay attention to the lectures, you should be fine in this class. The tests are pretty straight forward, but the tests definitely cover a lot of info. Office hours for this class were always held with the TA, not Dr. Libro.

Libro's lectures were very long, but she was always specific and answered questions. My only problem is that even if you understand the lectures well, the exams don't necessarily reflect the lectures, and there are only three exams that determine your grade. If you're fine with zero chance at getting an A then take this class. Libro is very nice!!

Professor Libro's class was by far more challenging than it had to be. Her lectures felt convoluted and it seemed like going online was the only reason why I managed to pass the class because it gave me adequate time to self-teach all of the material. She cares a lot you can tell, I just wish lectures could've been simplified so much more.

I found Libro's lectures super interesting. She knows what she's teaching and likes to incorporate lots of examples into her slides which I found to be very useful for learning the material. Her tests are not hard, if you pay attention during lectures you will do a fair job. Highly recommend Libro, she made learning like bio a lot more.

The most ineffective instructor I have had in my educational career. Nice person and clearly cares about what she's teaching, but has no ability to concisely explain concepts in an entry-level course. 81% of grade was determined by 3 exams that students were not prepared for. Lectures were a complete waste of time, but attendance was mandatory.
ratingTags: Graded by few things--Test heavy--Lecture heavy

comment: Required to take FINA2201? Choose another professor. Gooley's grading is completely unfair. He doesn't believe in partial credit for math problems and your grade is 85% based on exam scores. His lectures and the textbooks are totally different so you need to learn both. If you have an issue with your grade don't email him bc he has no patience.

The problem with Mark is that he noticeably has favorites in his class. He immediately assumes that if you do poorly on the first few assignments then youll do worse on the upcoming ones. Also, though this class was supposed to be a finance course, we really only did statistical analysis and was complete review of the Business Statistics course.

I had him for an in-person class about a year or two ago. He was probably the best teacher I have had at Northeastern. Classes were spent going over problems in-depth so that everyone could understand. Tests were long but weren't difficult if you paid attention in class and studied. He would have study sessions before tests.

He's a good professor. Those who try in his class and those don't put in much effort are fairly differentiated. He has a very unique style of teaching where he makes students (who understand the concept) in his class explain in layman's terms, which sometimes backfires and doesn't align with some students' learning. Overall very down to earth guy.

He makes getting a finance degree at NU feel worth it. He will answer any question you throw at him and is known to explain concepts as clearly as possible. 80% of the class like myself were people who had him before and loved his style so idk where bad reviews are coming from - 40% of his class got an A or A-, and the class average was an 85%.

You need to fight for a good grade. His homework is tough but thats why most of it is collaborative. One of the best things about Mark is that he replies within seconds which is unheard of from most professors. Tests are weighted heavily. I think he recognized who was raising their hands more on Zoom so he really tried not calling on them.

One of the best professors I've had at Northeastern in terms of how he teaches his material and helps us to understand it. However, he seemed to have a strong preference for a select few students when asked to participate in the online class, and he did not give extra time in the final to organize our document like he did with the midterm.

One of the worst professors Ive had at Northeastern. Expects the students to teach him the material and is very odd and condescending. His grading is awful, completely misunderstands everything and docks you down for it. Dont take this guy

I took his class online and I'm disappointed. His class was very disorganized and his feedback were more condescending and unhelpful than constructive. He tried to cover a ton of material very quickly in a short time period and the exam questions would be a lot more detailed. Really, really disappointed at how this class turned out to be.

very condescending towards students. Makes a lot of off the cuff remarks that are frankly rude and passive aggressive. He's not an understanding person, has strong favoritism for his white male students, and his tests are much more difficult than what he uses as examples in classes so it's difficult to end with a A or even a B+.

Very hard to follow in class and does not provide background/explanations for the concepts and material. Friendly guy but not great at encouraging engagement in class. Very disorganized and the only handouts he gives are practice problems which vary in format.
He uses his strange sense of humor to disguise the fact that he has no clear direction for his lessons.

Contrary to the most recent review, I attended every class, heavily participated, and worked hard but still think he is a poor professor. Finished with a great grade but that was all dependent on teaching myself the material. He does not walk you through concepts or teachings. All he does is practice problems where he picks on students to explain.

Has no clear direction with the class. Deviates heavily from the book yet provides no clear structure for his own methods/perspective. Tests account for 85% of grade. Does not really teach in class. Just asks for volunteers on practice problems.

I would recommend anyone take this unless they want to revel in self-doubt and anxiety throughout the entire course. He does not give answers to assignments you get back, continuously misinterprets you and makes you feel like an idiot. He is all about "assumptions". His grading mentality is not helpful.
ratingTags: Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.--Group projects

comment: Prof Gooley is a very kind, caring and smart prof who really wants his students to do well in class as well as in the real world. Always willing to help outside of class and even if you lack a finance background AT ALL like myself. He goes through class slowly, and his tests are FAIR - based on the material he taught us. Practice his problems!

Professor Gooley is the best professor I have ever been taught. He is respectful to everyone, caring students, and willing to direct students for the success in their career. He is knowledgeable and experienced in corporate finance. He not only teaches, but also exemplifies high-level work ethic, sharing, and being humble and open-minded.

Gooley is awesome. I had a class of 80+ students and he really tried to engage everyone. His explanations make a lot of sense, but you have to take the time to do the practice problems online before the test. Would recommend redoing the midterms to study for the final--he takes questions almost directly from the midterms. Amazing prof, 10/10.
Best class I've ever taken.

Gooley is a very nice person and well respected professor. Just do suggested problems in the back of the textbook and you will surely get at least a B+. Tests are not hard. He curves the grade at the end. Recommend taking his class and you will enjoy.
ratingTags: Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.--TEST HEAVY

comment: legend

I took valuation and value creation for summer 1 (Tue/Thurs class). Make sure you're all over the reading from the get-go or it'll be tough to catch up. He will expect a strong understanding of the material and makes you work hard for even a decent grade. Last week of class: 3 case studies due, followed by a cumulative final exam.
ratingTags: Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: Excent professor. If you come to class and just listen to him you can learn all the material. He really takes an interest in the students and will work one on one with you until you get it. Best professor I have ever had.

Gooley is an excellent professor. He really cares about his students and making sure that they understand the material. It's also great that he throws in jokes throughout class. The only thing is that he makes you work for your grade. His tests are difficult. Put in the time though and you should be fine!

Best professor I've had so far at Northeastern, I created this account just to give Gooley a good rating. Definitely worth taking this class if you're interested in personal finance. I will look to take classes he is teaching in the future. Thorough and willing to help. Work can be difficult, put in the time and effort and you will learn a lot

Finance can be dry but he explains very well and tries to engage.  Always available outside of class to help students and answers any questions.  Lots of prac probs in class, reading the book helps.  Missing class hurts.  Weekly homework sets due online but help with exams.  Mid/Final, 2-3 case studies, but he'll cxl asgnmts to cover exam topics.
He is a very good teacher and he makes sure everything was explained and tries hes best to help students.

Had him in Financial Management. Very very good and engaged teacher. Cares a lot about his students and tries the best to help, even with topics that are not subject of the class. I learned a lot. Nothing bad to say!

I had him for Financial Management. He is the best professor at Northeastern. He's a very clear and loud speaker. He gets to learn everyone's name and honestly does his best to help his students. His exams were not too easy, a bit hard. But I learned a lot of finance from him and I would definitely like to take another one of his classes!

He was my professor for introduction to Business. He tries to get to know each and every student in the class and is very helpful. It's been more than a year and he still remembers me and constantly encourages me to take his classes. Overall, very nice and helpful. Definitely would recommend.
He's a great teacher and he's very nice.  He wants all his students to do well

So nice! I loved her class - it wasn't really groundbreaking in any way but she really tries her best to make it interesting and FAIR to everyone. She gives extensions and gives you feedback early if you want or need.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--Graded by few things

comment: Prof Shecterman is extremely kind and cares about her students. The class goes from having no work for a few weeks at a time to a bunch of work all at once. Overall, it's a decently easy A if you do the work and show up to class.

Very fair, honest, respectful professor. Really good feedback, turned around quizzes within the week, and adjusted the grading policy based on feedback from the class. She put in extra time to get us our grades ahead of the school's COVID-19 Pass/Fail deadline which was something no other profs did. Highly recommend Yana!
If you're looking for a chill senior class, take this! Honestly just show up and do the work and you will get an A.
What can I say about Prof O Connor that he hasnt said himself. Be prepared to think outside of the box. I went from being a beginning team member and now I supervise a team.

For advertising and brand promotion, his class is a MUST. He will not assign busy work and you will learn however much effort you put in. One of the best professors I've had at Northeastern. Really cares about APPLYING material not just memorizing (which is just pointless in a rapidly changing major). Anyways- great teacher great guy!
Amazing professor. Would take again 1000 times over. Best professor I've had at Northeastern

Awesome prof! Interesting class examples, discussion boards are fluid but show that you have a grasp on the material and you'll do well. For this class there was a indiv paper/presentation and there was a group paper, I work full time and have other classes and did not feel it was an overwhelming amount of work.

I took his advertising elective and it was a really interesting class! He's really funny and energetic, so the class was never a drag. The projects are relatively easy and he's an easy grader. He's pretty laid back about attendance, and we never had homework outside of our presentations.

Great professor, absolutely hilarious, brings in guest speakers for networking opportunities, really wants his students to succeed BUT tests are hard are he knows that but they are curved and there are other aspects to make up your final grade

I wish I had taken more advantage of Chad's connections while I was in his class. He brings in people who are insightful and well-connected some come to those classes well-researched. He gives incredible feedback. For my final project, I had one group member who was difficult to work with, and he helped me navigate the situation. Very helpful!

Chad is the professor you would want to be friends with throughout your entire college and working career. He is incredibly well connected and gives insightful feedback.  Most weeks he will bring in a guest lecturer who is avidly decorated and successful in their fields. Great co-op connections. Best class I'll ever take in Northeastern.

The best. Smartest, most hilarious guy ever, so approachable, and has tons of experience. Chad has friends EVERYWHERE, and invites some to guest lecture, and no matter what you're interested in, he'll include it his teaching and make sure that you get someting out of the class. Take any class with him, you will NOT be disappointed. He's the man!

Chad is literally the best teacher ever!!! He is so funny, so friendly and very interesting. Always tells funny news stories that relate to the topic. He makes all of the material very clear and easy to understand. Definitely take him for Organizational Comm! Just go to the classes and read the case studies and you'll be fine.

If you have the option to take another Sociology professor....... DO IT. She is the toughest grader and when you meet with her to discuss what went wrong she makes you feel bad about it. It's as if she took the idea of " professors should want to help the student be successful" and interpreted it in the opposite way. Dropped my almost perfect GPA.

One of the best professors for drawing. Really gets you thinking about the medium in a different way. Students that aren't into abstract drawing struggle in the class but the dedication is worth it. Anyone taking it for an easy A shouldn't bother. She responds really well to effort and is super understanding.

One of the worst professors in my college experience. Top students receive C+s at best. If you don't devote all of your semester's attention to Julie's class, expect to get a D- or F. Requires 5-6 hours of mundane drawing every day. I love drawing, but her drawing assignments are beyond tedious.
Arrogant while grading. Expects you to know everything
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Lots of homework--Tough grader

comment: I got the top scores in exams and assignments after comparing with other students. However, a girl with lower scores than me got an A. But I just got B+. I believe the grading system is not fair

Really tough and rewarding class. Dr. Doug helped me get through the tougher projects. He is a Zoom master.

Super nice guy, good prof and funny too. The class is tough but if you work hard you can get a good grade. He'll drop 1 of the 2 midterms (or both if you do better on the final than on both) so you will end up with the best possible grade. Homework is worth the same as one midterm (20%) which will give you grade a boost as long as you get it done.

His exams can be difficult, but his grading system is extremely considerate. He drops the lower of the two midterms, and will even drop both if you do not do well, but the final would be weighted more heavily. Very entertaining and funny in class, and he does all tough problems step-by-step on the board. 10/10 professor

Professor Bai is a good and funny professor, however his exams are very hard an often curves. Make sure to study from all the extra packets he hands out and only takes attendance sometimes. You need to study, and if you do you can get a minimum B-.
ratingTags: TEST HEAVY--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Very good professor. Teaches finance from a more mathematical approach and goes over each topic in great detail making sure everyone gets it before moving on. Gives plenty of practice material, similar to what is on the tests. Tests can be very hard, so make sure to go over all his worksheets and office hours if needed.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria

comment: Bai is a classic college professor: his lectures are supplemental to what you should be doing on your own outside of class. He expects you to have knowledge of the chapters as he further discusses them in class. If you are dependent on learning in the classroom, don't take him. Little homework, very clear about exam topics, nice guy, but gotta work
Funny guy. Curve the average to B.

Bai truly cares about his students' well being and performance. If you work hard and show improvement, he will take that into consideration when calculating grades. The class section was very large and I do believe he had a bit of trouble communicating to different skill levels. Definitely take his class in a small section, he's a great guy
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Respected--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: HE IS A GREAT PROFESSOR. TRULY CARES ABOUT THE STUDENTS DOING WELL IN HIS CLASS. I HATE FINANCE AND HE TRIED TO MAKE IT AS UNPAINFULL AS POSSIBLE.  HE IS ALWAYS AVAILABLE OUTSIDE CLASS, HE IS A REALLY NICE PERSON THAT KNOWS HOW DIFFICULT THIS CLASS CAN BE FOR SOME PEOPLE THAT ARENT INTO FINANCE.  DO YOURSELF A FAVOR AND TAKE HIM. NICEST PROFESSOR

Apparently, I know half of my classmates didn't do well in this class. However, Professor Bai covered everything on the exam in class.  He made really clear of what you should know through the PPT. Make sure to take notes on every example he gives out in class, because they will most likely to be on your exams. One of my favorite professors at NEU!
ratingTags: Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria

comment: Nice guy, but horrible teacher. Half of the class was failing and MC questions were impossible. There seemed to be a large discrepancy between grades, i.e. those who came in with a solid foundation did well and those who didn't suffered.

I believe Spring 2016 is his first semester as a professor, he is okay, except the final exam, other were not so difficult, he curve the grade, but he doesn't explain the materials and lectures clearly. A lot of student in his class were confused. Well.. If you are a good student, take his class, you will be alright, but if you are not, probably no

Professor Moreno is very helpful in explaining course contents. Sometimes I got confused by the textbooks, but her explanation during office hours are very clear and easy to understand. The exams are very closely related to homework. Anyway, if you have any questions just go ask her. She is really nice and very willing to help.

My rating is based on her class when I took it, Fall 2015. I was not a good student, but this was the first acct class I enjoyed after my co-ops because it seemed more work-oriented and I learned a lot. She also called me out for being arrogant for the first time in my life and that's why I'm writing this years later. She was right. Thank you, Kim

the class is a walk through of oversimplified problems via powerpoint and then doing in class problems. these problems are fine but it's the only thing we have to study for the test, and the test is obscure questions that are not whats done in class. her grading is also biased - points back to some people but not others for similar mistakes
ratingTags: Tough Grader--TEST HEAVY--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: Very difficult tests. If you have a passion for cost accounting and you are willing to put in 5-7 hours per chapter when studying for an exam. Otherwise, avoid because it's simply stressful and too much work for little credit.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.--TEST HEAVY

comment: Tests are way too complicated. No study guide for exams. They are worth a lot of points so it affects your overall grade a lot. The questions are really different than the ones she gives in class and does not give additional practice questions. Do NOT take this professor. You get the feeling that she wants you to fail. Also, useless office hours.

Tough grader, makes exam really complicated. Even though they were so difficult, but I spent a lot of time on this class and I got 92 for exam 1, 85 for exam 2 unfortunatly, and 98 for the final. Sounds great right? But I got a 75/100 of my group p, that's ridiculous, we spent almost 1 month for it. If I had a chance, I WILL NOT CHOOSE HER CLASS!!!

I'm blown away by these positive reviews. Moreno was one of the most ineffective teachers I've had at NU. Each class consisted of brief 20-25 min review of chapter and then practice problems. Prof did poor job explaining answers to problems. Test questions like nothing covered in class. Refused to post materials to BB. Was rude during office hours

She is a tough but very fair teacher. The book does not seem necessary, but if you want to do well it is a must to have. The practice problems at the end of the chapters are the best way to review for her tests, and some of the questions are very similar to some of them. If you show interest in the class she is willing to do a lot to help you.

She's tough but fair. Ignore the textbook, read her class pack like the bible and you will be able to do well on her tests. Great sense of humor! Made class very interesting but DO NOT fall behind or you will not survive. Overall, one of my favorite teachers from northeastern (people who didn't like her didnt put in the effort necessary to succeed)

I understand why people give her a poor rating. The tests were hard, the project was extremely difficult, and it was not easy to get a good grade. However, she was very clear in class and always challenged you to learn. Put your effort and study hard, you should be fine. Don't just complain.

If I have two words to describe this "teacher" not the class: SHE BLOWS! The wording of problems are beyond help, since you won't understand what it is trying to say.  Also, she goes out of her way to make her questions overflowing with excess information.  So, if you want your dreams as an accountant crushed, then feel free to take this teacher.

1. Moreno is a good, but not an effective teacher. She over complicates the concepts and makes the test really hard, compared to class work. Every class, she would read through the power points and do in class problems. The problems in class are pretty fair. BUT, on the test, she makes everything super complicated. Bad teaching style, period.

Entirely unhelpful, she just went through powerpoint in class.  If you were even a couple minutes late, she would humiliate you publicly. This used to be a school for commuters, she had no sympathy  for someone who is working full time in addition to attending school.  Tests were much harder than any homework or in class examples.
