By far my favorite teacher so far at Northeastern. No powerpoints to sleep through. Clear examples that are gone over in class. To study for her tests I just went over the in-class packets again and aced them easily. Three tests and one project plus participation.

She is an awesome teacher. She gives out plenty of examples for each chapter so there is no way you can't understand it and if you still don't get it she is more than willing to explain it to you. She definitely keeps the class interesting. I recommend everyone take her

Like many courses, you get what you put in to it.  If you're looking for an easy A, this isn't the place.  If you want to learn a ton through application of accounting rather than staring at a book, Moreno is the professor for you
Poor teacher overall. Lacks patience, lacks expertise.
I went to Professor Karl's office hour twice. He is extremely willing to help, so if you get stuck by the homework, don't hesitate to ask him.
Class is based mainly on weekly homeworks and one project
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Accessible outside class--Lecture heavy

comment: Very good

One of my favorite professors at Northeastern. I had him for CS1100, and while my friends who had other professors were complaining, I had nothing to add. The class itself is mostly self-driven, so if you do not like that its an issue with the course, not the professor. Karl was available outside class time to help and is really such a kind person!

All learning is watching online lectures, then review is done in class. Watch them and take notes before class. Be prepared to be called on! Only 1 65 min class a week, but 10+ hours spent outside of class. Prof is quiet unless asked a question, but is very knowledgable and a sweet man if you talk to him! Hated class at first, ended up loving it!
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: for the required class for a lot of different majors, prof lieberheerr was good. if something was unclear, he would explain it and make sure you understood. but the class itself required a lot of work outside of the meeting time, but thats with any professor you choose to take it with.

This was the most work i've ever had for a course so far and it was only an 1000 level course. The professor doesn't explain anything. You are expected to teach yourself all the material by watching the online lectures before attending class. Class is once a week. Not nearly enough time to understand any of the material. Don't take this class.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: I took the class twice... the first time was during my very first quarter of graduate school and I dropped it after 2 weeks because it was hopelessly more complex than I could understand.   I took it again during my last quarter and was AMAZED at the depth of information Karl presented.  He remains one of my two best graduate school professors.

The man is an enigma. He has you learn algorithms through the use of a "game", which in theory is a very novel approach. In practice, it's sometimes a little silly (especially when you play by yourself). In class, he's fairly clear and is very receptive to people asking questions. Exams are open note.
The Game is useless and even if you ask exactly what you need to turn in for homeworks, you'll still be missing something. Avoid if possible, but you probably won't be able to.

This class is like starving to death. At first, you try and try to make it through the next day, but eventually, your stomach distends, and you hallucinate the laughing specter of Karl, mocking you, as you cannot even muster up the strength to swat the flies off of your face. You, and your GPA die, just as you came into this world, alone.

None of the comments on here are exaggerated. You will not believe how irrelevant and worthless this class is. You use buggy software and you may have grades that are LITERALLY random. He delegates ALL his work either to students or the TA, he does absolutely nothing. Class, tests, and homework have nothing to do with the course description. AVOID!

This class does nothing but indoctrinate the students into using a buggy and flawed piece of software called DemeterF. You will learn nothing about software development. A Student had to complain to the dean to get him to teach us testing methodologies, and even then we learned nothing. Avoid At All Costs, even if it means staying another semester.

NO. FALSE. NEIN. This class is an abomination. Epic fail. He doesn't teach anything about SD, like processes, version control, testing, SDLC, etc. Instead, he takes a math problem that he's interested in and forces you to use his buggy experimental framework to solve it. Expects you to be Java hackers and the TA often cancels office hours. AVOID!
Teaches nothing about Software Dev. Makes us do a project for his own gain. Assumes we're intense Java programmers even though we only took 2 classes with it (and learned nothing in them).
Horrible professor.  Just doesn't understand how much work he is assigning, or doesn't care.  Expect to spend upwards of 20 hours a week on the homework and expect to teach yourself too.

This class forces you to put in 25+ hours a week on the work.  The professor's apathy shines through in everything he does.  His website is a mish mosh of garbage which is bad when there's no real course text book.  Basically you're on your own in this class, don't plan on getting any help.  30+ hours a week will be spent on the project.

Tough class made tougher by a terrible instructor. He has some brilliant ideas about aspect-oriented programming, but he uses this course as a means of forcing them on you. There is no reason to use his language, except that it is required. Learned nothing about software dev. Terrible project spec, poor grammar. Gives helpful tips after due dates!

Absolutely ridiculous class.  No textbook, a TA who sounds like English is his 4th language, a stupid project that requries the use of buggy software, and to top it all off every single f---ing lecture was the same.  Whoever said this is the most important CS class at NEU was full of it.  I've learned more from watching pigeons fly around at Ruggle

Nice guy.  Willing to work with students and gives extensions on homeworks if asked.  Our TA didn't speak English very well but was a pretty easy grader. Tests can be tricky (mostly just fill in UNKNOWNs).  He loves demeterj and CSP a little too much...

The course was Secure Software Engineering. Or, at least, that's what it was called. It turned out to be a course in AspectJ and Demeter - really just him providing a forum for his students' research projects and trying to push AOP on everybody. I am told this is what ALL his classes are.
No Comments

His TA can not speak english.  His final project is retarted.  He teaches you DemeterJ wich is cool in theory but very buggy.  C's get degrees so hold on for the ride.  Its going to be a****ty semester.  You would think an upper level class in CS would teach you something useful but northeastern pulls through with another jackass professor.

He gets a reputation as being tough mostly because he is German (no lie, Germans tend to come across as dry and intimidating to Americans) and this course can be very demanding. However, this is THE most important course an aspiring programmer will take at NU and he does an excellent job presenting  theoretical and practical considerations of SD.

While the man is brilliant.  He is not a good teacher at all.  I think he just re-iterates over class notes he created years ago..When questions arrive..he seems befuddled.  And then we learn a language that's riddled with bugs.  WHY...

Brilliant man, wonderful professor. My only complaint is with the course itself, not with Lieberherr. The project was one that he had never done before, and didn't even know how to do himself. Talking to others who took his class, I guess this happens a lot. Surprised to find no Lieb bashers here!
No Comments

Work hard and you'll learn LOTS. Lieb. is a zen sort of guy, but if you get him talking you immediately pick up on his vast ability and experience. He is willing to help any time, but can be confusing at times. Great class. Do y'self a favor and take it.

Took Human Rights in Latin America and it was great. She had us read only the most important pages of readings and watch just a few mins of movies. The work is SUPER manageable. That being said, I learned a ton. She is an easy grader and gives extensions and great feedback. Graded by a paper, project, discussion posts, easy quizes, and participatio
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Accessible outside class--Amazing lectures

comment: She just seems completely worn out - no passion at all despite having knowledge on the subject, very disorganized, ultimately seems unhappy and it wears off on the students. She's also a very tough grader.

She's a good professor, and definitely very knowledgeable  about what she taught. I respect her greatly for that. However, she was a bit disorganized. The class is fairly easy, so long as you do the homework on time and show up. Be forewarned, the classes can seem to run on for a while.

I've had her twice, and truth be told, I'm conflicted about her. She is passionate and very knowledgeable about he subject matters, and she can be og great help. But she is also very unclear as to what she wants and does. She is also very disorganized...

Professor Corbett is extremely knowledgable about Spanish culture and focuses on Spain way more than LA, which I liked. Shows a lot of movies/ lots of reading, but not a lot of writing and she grades the group project at the end very leniently. Overall, she knew so much and graded well as long as you DID the homework on time. I'm taking her again.

Do not recommend. Shows lots of movies during class (which may sound easy but gets real boring fast). Has little interest in students, not personable, dry, and unprepared. Was looking forward to this subject but was very unimpressed with teaching approach. Waste of time and money.
She's an ok professor. Nothing really special, but not bad overall. She does have a very harsh attitude towards late homework and people who have right-wing political views, but globally.
Hard materials, she's not a hard grader though. I don't think I'd take another class with her, but she's not horrible.

This class is the worst class I have ever taken. The amount of work compared to the amount I learned is the most disproportional of any class i've taken. She was boring, monotone, and overall uninteresting. I used to be a history major and she made those professors seem exciting. Readings were due every class. They averaged 30 pages. Don't take it!

I genuinely can not recommend Professor Eidson enough: he is easily the best professor I've had. He's caring, kind and more than willing to help students at all times. His lectures are interesting and convey a lot of information in a thoughtful way. He also offers many ways to boost your grade, but does not overload you with work. 100% recommend!

Dr Eidson is amazing. He is kind, calm, and very approachable, gives great feedback and makes class discussions really interesting and funny. In 4612 you watch a bunch of movies and analyse them (amazing for a film buff, good fun for others) can't rage about Dr E enough, a really great prof (plus fair grader) HIGHLY RECCOMEND

Prof Eidson was a fantastic professor; one of the best I've had at NEU. He's caring and approachable and really wants all of his students to succeed in his class while also giving us skills we can use in research beyond his class.

If you like podcasts, you'll like this professor. Prof. Eidson seems to have adopted the speaking mannerisms of someone delivering a podcast. The downside is that he often overexplains simple concepts, which draws out the class.

prof Eidson is an alright professor, he makes the material easy and honestly does care about his students, he's just the slowest grader I've ever had. he even has TA that grades quizzes for him, but we get those grades back like a month after we've actually taken the quiz. That's the only frustrating thing about him , otherwise he'd get 5*.

One homework packet due before each test. Tests are exactly like the homework. You have to do Data Sets on SPSS and Excel which are a pain, but he grades them easily. Nice teacher. Lectures have plenty of examples.
He's an interesting professor but class never starts on time and he takes forever to grades exams.

Talks in circles. A lecture that could take 20 minutes takes 2 hrs bc he drags everything out. Promises that assignments/grades/study guides would be posted by a certain day and then didn't post until 3+ days later. His exams are mostly multiple choice with one open response at the end. Very nit picky and takes of points off for irrelevant stuff.

Dr. Eidson was a great professor for Developmental Psych this semester. Only 4 exams, 6 writing assignments, and no final which was super nice. He is always willing to help you and is very accommodating, just be sure to let him know if you have to miss class for any reason and he'll be understanding.

He's a really nice guy who just wants his students to succeed. He was the most accommodating professor I've had in terms of open office hours or scheduling things around my schedule. He made sure we really understood statistics rather than just memorizing the computations, which I appreciated.

This Professor really knows his stuff. I thought this class would be difficult but his teachings are interesting. Class style is mostly lecture but you can learn a lot. He is fair and respects his students on an individual basis. I would highly recommend him to anyone needing to take Cognition for their PSYC major or minor.

Dr. Eidson is a young professor who cares about his students. He is intelligent, but not uptight. He tries hard to make class interesting and gives detailed feedback on lab report drafts. I didn't like how he always returned them a few days to a week later than he said he would though- he should either make realistic claims or not make them at all.
not a very coordinated professor and has very vague guidelines
This professor is very bad, boring. Extremely tough - the class average was 75% and he is very rude with email responses. I do not recommend at all!

Very dry boring lectures + the prof has thick accent. Very exam heavy (30% midterm and 35% final that were very difficult), and lots of group case assignments that were tedious. Stopped going to lectures after second week since I wasn't learning chicken squat. I wouldn't recommend this professor to a sun-dried tomato. Avoid!

Definitely a class you have to put a lot of effort into 1) group assignments- a lot of work but only 10% of your final grade 2) purposely creates quiz and exam questions that are not the same as the homework or what we went over in class (so you're on ur own!) 3) His class is extremely hard to get an A in (it's a 95) and final is worth 35%

Here's my chance to be more specific. The worst professor I have ever taken. Lectures are desert dry, accent is impossible to understand, harsh grader, and the exams are absurd. As a result -- I wouldn't recommend this professor to a squirrel.
ratingTags: Graded by few things--Lecture heavy--Tough grader

comment: Took Professor Makolo's FINA 3303 (Investments) class online. His accent is heavy, and he uses powerpoint for 1 hour every class and writes unreadable chicken-scratch on the slides. I wouldn't recommend this professor to a ham sandwich.

Prof. Makolo's class is extremely easy to get an A-, but difficult to get an A. He was kind enough to cancel participation for students in different time zones. There are 5 case studies and multiple homework (answers are all online). The midterm and final exams were super easy (around 15 questions).

Accent takes some time to understand but overall he was a really good professor! He cares about his students and is willing to make changes to the format of his tests. Asking him questions via email or going to office hours is super helpful - He gives clear and detailed answers to help his students. An easy A-/A class with some work

Please do not be fooled by the lack of reviews here - his trace evaluations are far more accurate. You simply can't understand him with his accent. As unfortunate as this is - his accent + slow lecture pace make learning material through class near impossible - just know that if you can't understand him from his first class, it doesn't get better.
He is a really caring professor. Always available during office hours. You can drop one of the midterms and allows to bring cheat sheet. Overall fair grader.

He tries to make it understandable by going through multitudes of formulas but is actually more confusing. Overall though the subject matter is not hard to understand and he is a great resource during office hours. Honestly makes so much sense during office hours. Gives a cheat sheet during exams, and you can make your own. Not a hard professor.
ratingTags: Accessible outside class--Graded by few things--Lecture heavy

comment: Not a great professor. He has a very hard time connecting with the students and actually teaching them. This guy has done a lot of research and is very accomplished, but can't really convey the information in a way that makes the class feel meaningful.

Too many lectures, too tough of a grader, distant from helping students, very poor and non-detailed feedback. You can show up to every class and pay attention and study and it may not make a difference.

toughest grader in the world. Doesnt care if you get the correct answers, he will grade you based on HIS answers even if yours are correct. Group projects are graded very harshly and even if you do exactly what he asks for, you will get a B. You can speak to him and show him your project, he will say everything is perfect and give you a B maximum.

Toughest grader in the world. Doesn't care if you get the correct answers, he will grade you based on HIS answers even if yours are correct. Group projects are graded very harshly and even if you do exactly what he asks for, you will get a B. You can speak to him and show him your project, he will say everything is ok and give you a B maximum.

Honestly, decent workload but I'm not here to complain about that. This professor should not be teaching at NEU. If you want to learn how to think like Porter, take this class, you'll do great. If you want to learn about investments take ANYONE ELSE. I repeat, AVOID HIM.

This is the worst professor I have EVER had. He's never worked outside of academia and if you disagree with his investment theories/opinions he will heavily penalize you on your assignments. He should NOT be teaching at Northeastern. Literally take anyone else for investments this guy is a doorknob that claims he's too busy to help his students.
Not respectful, grade you based on the impression, you never know what he wants in the answer
ratingTags: Group projects--Beware of pop quizzes--Tough grader

comment: Professor is nice and passionate about investments. He's interesting but VERY specific. It's not easy to do well on the exams because you have to know what he is looking for, no what is "right". The 5 Group projects are difficult and time-consuming. There's a lot of extra credit opportunities, but you could probably do better with another prof.

Overall really like the guy. Very interesting to talk to during office hours. Tests are hard but if you pay attention in class and go to each one you'll be fine. Group projects are lengthy and time-consuming but they help you learn the material. A lot of opportunities for extra credit as well. Would certainly take him again.
ratingTags: Group projects--Beware of pop quizzes--Lecture heavy

comment: Do your share of the work and go to class because most exam questions come from lecture topics. He gives you plenty of chances for extra credit both from small assignments and from test questions. There are 5 or 6 major papers but as long as you do what he tells you you'll get an A on them, and they are group assignments not individual.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: Porter is all around a great teacher, but you have to come to class. He's one of the few that actually uses tegrity, but a lot of exam questions come from in-class problems that he runs through during the class. Overall, would take another class with him, make sure to take good notes during lecture, and you should be a well-earned A.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Lecture heavy--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: Professor Porter is one of the better instructors at Northeastern. Your grade will be determined by how much you pay attention in class as his tests are made from what he lectures on. There are 6 long, time-consuming papers throughout the semester that are rewarding if you put in the work. Overall, very fair and you will get the grade you work for.
ratingTags: Accessible outside class--Skip class? You won't pass.--Graded by few things

comment: Porter is a very fair teacher and getting a B in this class is very attainable because of the well organized study guides for the midterm. He will not give you a final exam if you like the grade they you have on your two midterms. Book is good for getting extra information but listening to lectures again through blackboard is a better way to study.

A pure academic through and through. Dude lectures and tests you on what he says. You're better off reading a transcript of his lectures than studying the text book or online resources. If you struggle with lecture based classes that have no visuals you should not take Porter.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--BEWARE OF POP QUIZZES--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: great professor

Really nice guy. He is patient. Need to work on the projects, took me lots of time. Useful class, you learned a lot. Exam questions are so random so you need to keep good notes and read the textbook. Choose him if you want to learn.
ratingTags: Respected--Get ready to read--SO MANY PAPERS

comment: Good guy; definitely makes you work to earn your grade. Go and see him as much as you can or else you can get lost pretty quickly. You have to attend every class as well as read the textbook in order to truly grasp the material. Tests are tough, but fair. If you want to leave class knowing your stuff, he's a great professor.
his lesson is hard to understand. you'll mess up cuz he doesn't follow text book. Too many assignments (2 short essays per week and 6 very long very hard papers )
avoid
Really really long assignments!!
really long assignments

The entire lectures are made up of her explaining visualizations, and she's great at it. But from homework 5 and after you are required to code in D3 which the TA teaches for about 40 mins once a week. I'm sure he was great but just not a good teacher, and the starter codes are not enough to complete the homework that make up most of your grade.
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Group projects--Beware of pop quizzes

comment: This professor is so bad that EVERY STUDENT in my section opted to attend this class online even though we all had the option to come in person. She is an extremely tough grader and is very condescending. Her lectures were long, boring, and not helpful at all. She always ended class at least 10 minutes late, and yet somehow was always behind.

I believe he may be caring for students, but really not a fan of his lecturing style. He doesn't give syllabus, just puts everything on Canvas, and he gives very abstract and hard-to-follow recommendations instead of direct instructions. Heavy workload, need to spend out-of-class times for 3 extra meetings every week (avg 1hr for each).

Think carefully before you register for his class. Heavy workload. There are four weekly meetings for his class and projects; however, it should be only 2 meetings. He takes participation seriously and even rewards people for saying something meaningless. The class is formated as discussion and he uses third-party software to do the teaching.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Graded by few things

comment: If you value your sanity please don't take tag. Even if it means dropping the schm concentration please don't take him. He forces participation in the dumbest ways, rewards people for sucking up to him. Never stops talking, but also never teaches you anything.
ratingTags: Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.--Lecture heavy

comment: Lots of personal anecdotes and not out-of-textbook style of lecturing (highlights what's important and might be on exam however). Only 2 tests, 25% each, so study very well. Exam guide is written by a student during review time, so pray you have someone who do their job well or take all notes yourself. Take good notes and contribute in class.

I'm extremely surprised Tag is a 2.6 right now. He is very explicit with feedback for you and getting feedback for himself to make the class better. I found his midterm to be extremely easy and don't expect the final to be hard. He makes listening in class really easy and even outlines when something he is saying is super important. Very Friendly
Workload is not heavy, very understanding of students and the circumstances they are in. Lengthy time for simple projects
He relays real life example (which he has a lot) back t cass and prepare you for the work force. Very very hands on class and is open to feedback. Not your typical out of the textbook professor

Probably the worst professor in all my years of education, and that's considering my love specifically for logistics. His classes are extremely boring, he doesn't teach anything important and transfers almost all of his teaching responsibilities to students, at the same time being very harsh on attendance. Would recommend avoiding him at all costs.

Challenging, gratifying style of teaching. Having teaching experience myself this is what I noticed. Great experience in real business environment. Does not use classic academic approach. He will give you a case without laying out the method to solve it, so you will struggle but care about learning the method. Challenging but builds confidence!
ratingTags: Participation matters--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Would take again

comment: Doesn't teach anything, unrealistic mandatory participation but barely gives any opportunity. You will not know where the test is coming from

He is literally the worst professor ever. He pretends and talks a lot about how much he cares about his students. BUT! BUT! Not at all. Don't come to him if you are about to bring him more work. DO NOT THINK HE IS NICE. Literally the worst professor ever, ever.
Professor used to teach undergraduate, now teaching for MBA graduates, many people are not satisfied. Not sure why Northeastern allocating under graduate professor to MBA graduates.

This professor doesnt prepare you well for case studies or either finals.  Invites couple of guest lecturers. Shows that he is very concerned about his students but he is not. Very baised towards few students in the class.  Wouldnt recommend him.

I took her Calculus - Business/Economics course as a part of NUAccelerate. Her lectures are mind numbing and the examples she explains are far from the difficulty of the homework. I basically taught myself the entire curriculum. Furthermore, she includes a semester long group project with vague instructions doesn't provide any clarification or help

Professor Bai is a nice person, but she is awful at explaining. If you are good at Calc or have previous knowledge, then this might not be too bad. However, if you are average at Calculus, do not take the class with her. Moves quickly, explains badly and very confusing. Do not recommend.

Professor Bai is the best math professor I've ever encountered. She is very helpful and willing to answer any questions. Her lectures are very clear and homework are relatively easy. She gives very clear instruction on quizzes and exams. Be sure to practice the questions in her "class pak" then you will definitely achieve high score.

I took the course as part of the NUstart Program in the fall semester. Overall her lectures and example problems she used did not match the level of difficulty of the homework/exams. Group projects are a good way to learn how to apply the concepts learned and gain deeper understanding. TAs did a majority of the work in this class.

I gained a lot of friends through this class because we struggled through her poor online lectures and communication together. If you're expecting a helpful email, don't. She either won't reply because she's in the wrong, or she'll reply with "email your grader" aka the TAs. The TA's do all the grading and are much more helpful than Prof Bai.

Really nice but awful at explaining. The lectures are so easy but the homeworks and the quizzes are so much harder. Wouldn't recommend if you have not taken calc in highschool or struggle with math in general.

I took this class through NUStart. The material was okay considering it was Calculus and I had taken a precalc course in high school. Either way, she is very nice but can be hard to understand. Her teaching style is not my favorite. I only passed because I went to many office hours with her, TA's and an another tutor.

I'm not sure why her recent ratings are low, but Professor Bai is sweet and interpersonal throughout the lectures despite the online format due to COVID-19. Textbook reading isn't needed as she provides ppt slides and worksheets (which the tests/quizzes are based on) and there aren't any graded hw assignments. Doing textbook problems will save you

Honestly, one of the worst professors I have ever had at university. She does not teach and you better expect to teach yourself EVERYTHING. All she does it copy notes on to the board at a very quick pace. Don't expect tutoring help or any other help either.
Puts a quiz the day back from spring break.
Long and boring lecture. Depend on yourself
She is the best professor to take for 1231. She very good explaining and as long as you pay attention you should get an A-/A.

Overall, she's nice, but her class can be very boring because she lectures at the board the whole time. Her explanations can be confusing at times, but if you work hard and make an effort it's an easy A. There are quizzes every single week and the homework is all online but isn't due until the end of the semester.

Took the course as a 2nd year and my class was mainly freshmen. they were sometimes really rude to her, but Professor Bai was a sass master and shut them down. She was very willing to give one-on-one help and allowed you to correct mistakes in your group project for points back. I enjoyed her teaching so much that I took her for MATH 1231 as well.

Rekha is one of the best math professors I've ever had! She is easy to understand, although she can be quiet at times. She has students do problems in class -- they aren't for credit, but they help. She is very available in office hours and is kind to students; she'll really put in extra effort to make sure you understand. Quizzes are reasonable.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Amazing lectures

comment: NICE PROFESSOR BUT MAKES THE COURSE SEEM HARDER THAT IT IS.

Precalc with her was honestly a huge waste of my tuition money. Yes the class is easy, but maybe a little too easy that it makes it hard to take it seriously and stay on track. She is very condescending if you are a weak math student, and won't reply emails or provide extra help to students outside of very limited office hours.
This class was a show up, sleep for 100 min, and get an A. I couldn't stay awake in the class, and the professor stretches out about 15 min of material for the full class time.

I saw some people mentioning her strong accent, but it's really not a big deal. She's very nice and really chill. On the rare occasion that people jokingly express being stressed in the class, she'll just calm everybody down. Also, she's really thorough when introducing mathematical concepts.

This is my second class with Professor Bai. I think she has a very specific teaching style which works for some people and not for others. Fortunately, she worked for me really well. She gives many quizzes but they are short and she will tell you exactly what to expect. I think she is a great teacher for some but not for others.
This class was comically easy. If you have a calc requirement, definitely take Rekha. There's no reason you shouldn't get an A in this class.

Rekha Bai talks in a pretty thick Indian accent, but if you pay attention relatively well and go to class most of the time it is an easy A. Quizzes are assigned regularly, and the lowest quiz grade is dropped, so it is easy to bring your grades up. Would recommend taking math with her if you are a business or econ major!

Very unhelpful for those who struggle with math, doesn't reply to emails. Yeah, there tends to be the students who are more math savvy who pretty much just fly through the class and grades in success. She is dull, difficult understand and approach, and has no personality to try and be more approachable. Her explanations are unclear.
A little hard to understand at first but you get used to her after a while. She is very very helpful and sweet. Loved her!!
Great teacher! She's a little hard to understand at first, but pay attention in class and do all the homework (not graded) and you'll do very well

She might not be the best orator, but her classes are well organized. Though it seems like she just got off the boat she has a lot of experience. She's approachable, open to questions and brings clarity to the subject.
GREATTTT Professor

Definitely a good teacher who cares for her student's success and who, despite her strong accent and monotonous voice, explains everything very well. Average grader and has lengthy office hours. Just do the work, revise the material several times and you'll do well.

Ok. I hate the class but with her its easy yet very boring. No need to do the hw or anything. Key to succeeding would be to master the guide and practice problems they make you buy. Do it the night before and you are set. Quizez are easy, Mid terms are okay but the FINAL is challenging to say the least.

She is a solid teacher. Not exactly interesting or the best but definitely teaches you the material. Pay attention, come to class, and if you need it schedule office hours because she doesnt exist on campus otherwise. I suggest read the book if you dont understand then ask in class. She likes questions. She has an accent-meh.

She teaches in a very organized, logical sequence, but does not mind stopping to address questions. She provides time for in class practice and circulates to make sure that everyone can do the work, even if they do not ask for help. She always graded quizzes in a timely fashion and very fairly. She is also flexible, moving the quizzes around.

Ms. Bai was a good teacher, she made everything very clear while she taught. You really only need the book for half of the class so if you can just share with someone in class you're golden. The final is cumulative so you need to make sure you study hard. Overall an easy class.
She is a tough teacher, she WILL make you work a lot and she has a difficult accent to understand. Nevertheless, her class was fun and interesting. Likes to assist students in case they struggle.

This class is soooooooooooo easy, the quizes and the mid term are jokes. she basically gives you the questions and changes the values in the tests. but she is a terrible teacher, it is impossible to learn calc from her.
Overall a good teacher. could be a lot clearer and more caring. If you are not doing well in the course, don't expect her to help you at all, so work really hard.

The class is easy, mainly because I took advanced calc in hs. Attendance is not mandatory, but she hates people who doesn't show up for class. I got the 9:15am slot so a lot of people never showed up and she was always pissed. Fair grader.
Has an accent. Very nice lady and will help you. Like 7 quizes she drops the 3 lowest. Final and midterm are hard but an overall easy class. Great Prof!

She'll like you and make an effort to help you if you show up everyday. she was really mean to the kids that didn't show up. She likes students that work hard even if your not particularly skilled. Hard to understand.

I usually struggle in math, but Prof Bai was very clear and made sure I knew the subject matter. She gives you review the day prior to a quiz and it is almost identical to the quiz itself. drops the lowest two quizzes. One of the best math teachers I've ever had.
Great professor. Small accent but she is nice and understands where your coming from. Teaches well.
If you've taken high school calculus this class is a breeze.  She's a nice lady too, and you can probably get away without buying the book.

An extremely easy class if you do her review worksheets. They are practically copies of the actual quiz. She's a very nice lady, but the class is far from exhilarating....pretty boring in fact. But hey, can Calculus really be exciting?
easy class, amazing professor...

Her accent is not hard at all to understand. She is a really great professor and will gladly help you if you need it. Her quizzes are very fair - you get a review before each one that is exactly like what will be on the actual quiz.
Nice lady, if you go to class, it's easy to get an A. A little bit hard to understand her accent, but not too bad. Her quizzes are exactly like her quiz reviews.
She is alright. Doesnt look like she likes what shes teaching. A bit like a robot. Speaks with a monotonous voice. But doesnt grade to hard.

If you have to take a calc class i would definitely recommend Bai! The project was easy and the quizzes were exactly like the quiz review she gives you for homework. I had a solid A in the class until the final, which i failed and brought me down to a B. The final is 40% of your grade and is MUCH harder than you will think.

Prof. Bai is a sweet, quiet Indian woman (slight accent, no problem).  If you want to learn real calculus, then this class is not for you.  Besides the few basic calculus concepts, I often felt like it was 10th grade algebra and not college calculus.  However, since the course is required, get Bai, it's an easy class made easier by an awesome prof.
professor Bai was a great teacher just do the class packet cuz thats basically all the quizzes are based on. Her final is hard and its worth 40 percent of your grade

Great math teacher. Nice woman, who wants you to do well. Takes attendance. Uses the textbook, but you really don't need to buy it. I stopped looking at it after the first few weeks.  Course only gets semi-difficult towards the end when the actual calculus begins.  Distribution was... 15% group project, 30% quiz, 15% midterm, 40% final.
Nice professor, very helpful, easy, clear, no homework.
she's a great teacher. EXCEPT for one thing. you better be damn certain that you do well on the final. my avg in the class was an 82.2 but my overall grade was a D+ because of my final.
No Comments

Awesome professor. Wants her students to do well in the class. I never had a problem understanding her. I wasn't that interested in taking calc at first and it ended up being my best class this semester.
Great teacher, not totally easy, but no really really hard, i liked her overall!

Amazing woman.  She's a truly caring teacher who knows how to convey her material.  I paid attention, did my homework and got an A.  I don't see what everyone is talking about with her accent.  She's just as understandable as anyone I've ever talked to and I don't know one person in my class who had trouble comprehending her.

good teacher, has an accent but still understandable. sometimes move a little fast but just ask her to slow down. quizes alwasy exactly what she says they will be. so far as a frosh, best teacher ive had

She was a teacher that yes, did have an accent, but i didn't find it to be a problem, while she did move fast it was a fairly reasonable pace, her tests were always what she said they were going to be, no bull, overall good teacher
I've never liked math, but calculus is easily my favorite class this semester b/c prof. bai makes it simple and clear- plus she's really nice and can be funny! I love those quiz reviews
couldnt be any easier- gives practice quizzes that are the exact format of tests, even for midterm/final.  lets you drop 2 worst grades.  very nice woman.
All the quiz reviews are pretty much the same as the quizs you get.  She goes over anything you need help in during class and is very helpful.  Plus she's really nice.
Excellent teacher. Goes slow and makes sure all students understand material. Goes over quiz material, project is easy and lectures are clear.
No Comments

i could not undestand a word she said, i had to change classes, and besides, she moves extremely quickly, i was doing bad becuase of her accent, and her rapid explanations and assumptions that everyone knows what they are doing.
Quizzes were easy, but I still learned stuff from her class. She is soft spoken, but covered all the material needed to do well on the final, great teacher.
This woman is a terrible teacher. All you idiots who rated who already obviously did not double check the notes she gave us because half the time they were WRONG. Bad bad teacher.
The class is boring, shes a straight-forward teacher. You have to remember to practice doing the problems and pay close attention the 1st 2 weeks, or else the class is a struggle.
great teacher.... quizes, midterm, and final are exactly like the practice versions she gives you... hard to understand but very helpful
a little hard to get used to but an easy 100
Very Easy Class. Very Easy Teacher. Practice quizzes are exactly like actual quizzes. Honestly this is the easiest calculus class that you will ever take!!
Test and quizes are the same as practice quizes she gives out in class.Class is boring as hell and the group project sucks

She can't speak very good english, but she knows what she's talking about.  The practice quizzes are EXACTLY like the real quizzes, which rules.  She is fair and she doesn't take attendance.  I have never taken calc before, and I'm doing well!
This class would have been a whole lot easier if she spoke fluent english. Class is pretty easy. Gives you practice quizzes that are the same as the quiz you take.
No Comments
No Comments
IF you have trouble with your grades and try to email her do you get a response NOOOOOOOOOO definetly not cool
Nice teacher. Clear and understandable. Easy quizzes and always prepares you before tests.

Professor Carr is a very arbitrarily hard grader. You must act in such a specific way that the enjoyment of acting just disappears; there is no room for creativity at all. It feels like you must be "on your game" every day, or you're bound to not succeed in this class. This class leaves little leeway to those that are introverted. Don't take.

Teaches the intro to acting class in the weirdest ways, allowing almost no room for other ways of learning how to act. It's like that one math teacher that forced you to do every step her way in middle school, and his grading is another level of nonsense. Feels like he stretches the tiny mistakes you make into taking off points. Don't take him.

Super nice, super good at actually teaching the content and you get to see a lot of cool plays in this class. Kind of weird how specific he can get with grading stuff sometimes, some of the grading can seem arbitrary. Likes things done exactly how he tells you, which in a theater class doesn't leave a lot of room for creativity of presentation.

Jonathan is a very nice and interesting professor but he's a harsh grader for an intro level class that anyone can take. If you don't write the papers exactly how he imagines It should be written he'll give you a bad grade. The final group project is also rather advanced for an intro level class. Beware if you're looking for an easy NUPATH.

Jonathan is amazing. I've worked with him on theatrical productions before, but this class was great too. He knows theatre as well as anyone and is more than effective when teaching it. He's sometimes a little less than receptive to outside opinions though. If you don't write your papers the way he would write them, your grade won't be as great.

I have taken two classes with Jonathan now and loved both of them. He was always very clear and helpful inside and outside of class. It isn't unusual for him to respond to your emails within the hour if you need his help. As far as grading, he makes it extremely clear what he expects from you but  wants you to excel at it. Great no nonsense prof.
Best class I've ever taken

Probably the friendliest and most approachable prof at NU. He really knows his stuff and wants you to improve as an actor. He tries his best to make the class fun, which I thought it really was. As far as being a tough grader: If you complete the assignments as required and put in rehearsal time (which shows in your scene) you'll do well.

I love Jonathan. Yes, you have to give him a lot for you to give you a good grade, but you want to give him all that you can. Participation for this class is everything, but you can't be in an acting class without expecting to act. There is a significant amount of rehearsal expected outside of class, but only in the second half of the semester.

Sure he grades you on participation, which can be annoying, but it helps to keep you involved in the class. Jonathan is one of the nicest and most lighthearted professors I know, if you ever don't understand something or if you want to get more involved in theatre he's ready to help.

Jonathan was an amazing professor with an obvious passion for the class and the material. He is extremely fair in his grading. He expects you to bring your best to class everyday. Minimal assignments but each is worth a large part of your grade. Text book seems useless at some times but overall the class was very enjoyable.
The class is fun and you do meet nice people, but the professor is a very strict grader and demands participation. Would not recommend that you take him.

there are quizs based on two books and some really annoying papers. Sometimes the class is really boring, you are supposed to spend more than 12 hours each week on rehearsal. Not a easy class to get A- and not too much fun. The professor doesn't care about you that much.

Unless you really like theatre, take a different elective. He demands participation and class discussions make me fall asleep. Also, he made it mandatory to go see a theatre piece he directed (which you had to pay for). Would not recommend for people looking for a fun elective

Hard Grader.. He demands participation so if you are expecting to relax in this class, forget about it. It is true that it is interesting and he makes the class fun, but it is definetly not an easy A. Loads of work and group work, won't recommend it if you dont like theater or are just willing to fill the humanities req.

Jonathan is super nice but you really need to think of something intelligent to say. If you say something stupid,then you'll feel embarrassed. Class participation is important! This class is so easy to pass if you show up and participate and study for the midterm and final. He is a really nice, understanding teacher and he is very smart!

Attendance is definitely required. Participation is definitely required. And you better read the assignments. The good news is he makes discussions interesting and you actually want to read the books he assigns. It's a good class.

I love this professor! I have taken both art of theatre and the&soc and enjoyed both immensely. I'm a pharmacy major but it was a nice change of pace from the sciences. He's really passionate about the subject, discussions are thought provoking, and every class was worth going to. Attendance mandatory. Not hard if you actually do some work. Easy A

Ridiculously hard grader. As a pharmacy major, I took this as an arts/humanities elective thinking it would be an easy A. It is far from an easy A. I had much harder classes that I didn't work nearly as hard in that I received an A for, including my core classes, but I worked my butt off for his class and I only got a B+. Ridiculous.

Prof. Carr, I believe, is well aware that 50% of his class is there simply because NU requires an art course. He does his best to make sure that students actually learn something, through the attendance policy and surprisingly difficult exams - as long as you keep up with reading (!) and go to class you will be fine.

Very nice, smart, funny. I never wanted to skip, which is fortunate, b/c attendance is mandatory. Knows so much from personal experience, and explains things clearly. For 101 great to have, whether or not you know anything about theatre. You learn about all kinds and sides of theatre and he lets you share your opinions, rather than dictating them.

He does not only rate on how often a student participates, but also on how effective their comments are. I found this very demeaning because he was very rude when someone did not fully understand something. I felt that his grading system was unjust and he is the reason I am switching out of theater as my major.

Interesting professor, makes a lot of jokes. I enjoyed the discussion based class. My only complaint would be that even he admits that his grading is tough and somewhat subjective. There are barely any graded assignments, so it's hard to tell what he is looking for. Participation is a large part of the grade so if you're shy you might have trouble.

Professor Carr is awesome. He is definitely one of my favorite professors at Northeastern. Attendance is mandatory but he makes class really interesting; it's never boring. He has a great sense of humor and he is always willing to help. I definitely recommend this class to anyone who wants to fulfill a requirement or is interested in the theatre.
He's such a nice professor and he always cares about his students. It's fun to be in his class.
He's such a nice guy, and he's so passionate about what he does. I recommend him to anyone.

He's an incredibly nice professor.  I'm not an avid fan of the theatre and took it just to fulfill a core requirement, but he got me into the whole idea of the complex world of theatre.  The reading's dry, but even he admits that.  Good class over all.

He is mad chill. Attendence is manditory and you cant be late. Acting is a smaller class, and he cracks jokes + pokes fun at students all the time. Awsome guy. Not really a hard grader, but def not an  easy one either. Its really hard to get an A in his class, but its fun and interesting just the same.
No Comments

Great Class! Carr is an awesome prof, and I would recommend him to anyone.  His lectures actually make me want to go to class... and that's rare! Class topics are interesting and engaging, worth taking for any reason - but also satisfies Core requirements
Real Nice guy. He seems to know what he's talking about. The class is fun and easy, and as long as you show up and aren't an idoit, you'll do well. Attendence is manditory for this class.
Really great guy.  Knows his stuff, and makes class fun.  Definitely recommend taking any of his classes regardless of your major.
No Comments
Worst college Professor EVER. Never take her class or work with her. Beware Bad Experience.

One of the worst professors I have ever seen. Her accent is very thick, you cannot understand what she is saying. Be prepared to teach yourself the material. If attendance was not required, I wouldn't show up and it wouldn't have made a difference. DON'T TAKE THIS CLASS IF YOU DON'T HAVE TO.

Worst professor I've ever had! Threw more work at us than in any other class, was all over the place as far as expecations one time we didn't summarize then he graded us poorly and said we should be summarizing. One time he said we don't need to tie in the chapters then we needed to. Gave 1 day deadlines! Had no respect for working professionals
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--Tough grader

comment: David is knowledgeable but he does require a lot for your effort. His syllabus instruction is vague and he is a conventional teacher, meaning he will take your points off for small things (that don't even say in the syllabus).
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Get ready to read--Lecture heavy

comment: Reading requirements are huge and most are not related to what you are graded on. Discussion forum topics are interesting. Only seems to be one correct conclusion to case studies though. Cultural theme and book theories must be included in all posts or risk lower grade for getting too far off topic. He does contribute a little to discussion.

At first I was a little worred.  This was a huge course load, especially since its an elective.  Half the class dropped after the first week because of this.  Once I got into it, the course load was actually manageable, and he gives great feedback on all your work.  He is interesting, and very helpful. If you listen to feedback, he will help you.

Late to classes, late to finish the classes, late or doesn't respond to emails at all, unclear grading criteria, not using time efficiently; you have to make up with extra videos he posts (which is also late). Had an unbelievable time in this course. Not recommended but only professor out there for DS2001 Business.

Guided me through the language program to receive a BA with specialty in German, Spanish and Russian. This degree was in addition to a BS degree received in the same year. (94). Both degrees have served me well and the languages have given me a distinct advantage. Well worth the investment in time and tuition. Great professor this one.

He likes to go on tangents during his lectures about how little our generation knows. I'm sure you'll know what a vacuum tube is by the end of the semester (we got that lecture multiple times). Weekly blackboard posts are your grade, with two announced quizzes the whole semester (fairly easy quizzes but he doesn't ask what he put on the study guide

Awesome professor. Doesn't feel like you're learning anything because he makes it interesting and fun to talk about. He gives clear study guides for each tests, so it's pretty easy if you just pay attention to that.
Great Teacher.  He made a mistake when he printed the final and gave us all a 100 on it.  AMAZINGG!!!

Great professor. Really knowledgable and well-traveled. He reminds me of a cooler version of everyone's grandfather. Goes off topic ALL the time, but it's always fun. He his TA at the time--Professor Jarvis Chen--is super cute! I have no idea how he got a professor to be his assistant, but that must mean that Professor Robinson is highly regarded
Hopefully Jarvis co-teaches this steamy class every semester. It's like a friggen sauna in that class. sooooooooooooo appealing and REALLY stimulating...
My favorite professor of all time, I want to rent him as my grandpa.
the man, the myth, the legend !
Loved this class.  He goes off topic alllll the time, but the discussions are great.  We spent one class talking about what it's like to be high because he's never been high and wanted to know.

Interesting guy, gets off topic ALL the time, but still cool discussions. Two tests based entirely on lectures, so go and take notes and you will be fine. If you mess up, he allows you to write a paper to replace your lowest grade. The only problem: we only studied French lit and he tells you what he thinks and doesn't let you finish sentences.

Really interesting and funny man. If you get a chance take his class, he does go off on tangents but we always had really interesting conversations. If you like a structured class he might not be for you, doesn't follow the syllabus strictly and kind of figures it out as you go. Really nice and funny man

Very interesting class.  Class is all discussions on random topics, many tangents, many interesting things discussed.  reading in 3 books is the only work for the semester....read and come to class and the midterm and final will be easy and if you by chance mess up, easy paper to replace a grade
nice guy and interesting class. shows some movies. midterm, final and paper, but he counts the best 2. reading is assigned, but only one book was the most important. good class!

Nice guy, the tests are based on his lectures so make sure you take good notes. He tends to digress a lot, but just remember all the terms he uses. The readings weren't too bad and weren't long, just make sure you read them. Participate a lot and make sure he knows your name, if he does then you're golden.
Great Professor! Very Interesting, rarely on topic, but still a very fun class. Little work but lots of reading!

This class got old FAST.  Read 80 pages in 4 different books a week, never had any assignments except for one midterm where we had to remember all of it. Chugging Monster to do my final paper was the most fun I had involving that class.  H-Brook is very intelligent, but he just expects too much from the students.

Really good prof--knows just about everything there is to know about anything. Class discussions were always random and rarely on-topic but interesting nonetheless. Attendence and participation is factored into your grade but as long as he knows your name you're set.

Don't take French Culture unless you like reading until your eyes fall out.  It is actually ridiculous how much reading there is, but then again, we rarely get any other assignments.  Class discussions are always interesting, he goes on tons of tangents.
He should be teaching a geometry class, he goes off on so many tangents! (bad joke, I know, but it's true) Seems like a pretty cool class so far!

i like that he expresses his own views in class but encourages us to make up our own mind. His tangents are usually entertaining as well, even though I still dont understand why it mattered what type of car some guy from an old tv show drove...downsides are i kinda expected a more diverse pick of literature, it seems like all the novels are french.

Awesome class, really interesting, really laid back, really easy exams, really interesting discussions, wish he taught more classes cause I would take them if he did, really knowledgable, funny, great class to take "just because"
The novels were interesting but we spent too much time on them, I became bored very quickly.
Professor Robinsin is very knowledgeable in the subject.  He has a very informal teaching style. There were minimal assignments and seemed to be a liberal grader.

Although we rarely followed the sylabus, this class was interesting. Mr. Robinson is really intelligent and welcome to new ideas from students. The book choices were great, however I feel that there could have been more of an intl collection. Most books were originally in French
Cool Guy
Prof. Robinson is a really great guy.  He is low-key, but very knowledgable.  Class is always interesting.

Professor Robinson's a great professor. He is very openminded and accepting of everyone. He conducts his class very well, and loves to chat with students afterwards. I would definitely recommend him over most other professors.
Professor Robinson is very helpful. He is funny and a very good teacher. He has weekly quizzes and he is very big on participation. A very good teacher.

Exams were much more difficult than the material we covered in the lectures, the project was very hard, and he is an extremely tough grader. Power is rude and will show no empathy no matter what your situation is.

I wouldn't recommend him at all. In the first class, I thought he was going to be the best professor of the semester but instead he was the worst. The class may seem easy but his tests are not. He doesn't like giving A's, he usually gives only B's. VERY tough grader. He will never give you 0.01 points to have a better grade, so don't even ask.

Professor Power will make you work, but you will learn a ton. Expect every class to always be a mix of 70% his lectures and 30% two group presentations. The course includes a simulation game which is an excellent way to apply the info you learn throughout the year. An A is attainable if you do all your work, but beware he will make no exceptions.
Professor Power gives clear and understandable lectures but the tests and projects are a lot harder than the class material. He is a tough grader and will call you out in front of the class.

Professor Power's real world experience makes the lectures more interesting and easier to understand. Besides the tests and one project, everything is graded on completion. He is always open to answering questions from students during lectures, so take advantage of this. As long as you give him respect, he is understanding and will help you out.

not a nice guy. Yelled at someone for using the bathroom too much, gives absolutely no leniency for anything for any reason. Assigned a group project that takes 8-10hrs. only gave 8 days to work on it, had to be worked as a group. The project opened online the first fay of thanksgiving break, so we only had 3 weekdays to do 10hrs of group work
ratingTags: Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria

comment: The class is extremely easy for tests, but the bulk of your grade is subjective from participation and presentations. His grading scale is only between 84 and 88. If you do a bad job you get an 84.... if you spend 10 hours on something and it is spectacular you get an 88. This makes it extremely easy to get a B+ / A-, but difficult to get an A.

Power was a great professor, one of the best I've had at NU. He made Supply Chain really interesting and showed that he cared about the topic, but also cared about making sure we understood the material. He was also great about giving real world examples for just about everything. 3 Tests, non cumulative, final project simulation instead of final.

If you want to learn about supply chain, take this class. If you want an A, don't. Power knows everything about supply chain and you can learn a ton from him, but the course is super fast paced and his exams are next to impossible. His questions are confusing and sometimes aren't related to in class material at all. Only take if you're a SCHM conc.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment: Prof Power is a super nice guy and is very accessible outside of class. However, he makes his tests so hard (and will tell you that on day 1) that you cannot learn Supply Chain past memorizing and forgetting it for the tests. It is a shame because the subject was interesting. There are WAY easier profs.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.--TEST HEAVY

comment: Most difficult intro class taken so far! He tells you at the very beginning that class is not easy. Strict grader and tough on class policies. Heavy use of powerpoint so lectures can be boring. On the plus side he does have a lot of experience in the industry so he does make it relatable. Tests are super difficult so READ ahead of time! Good Luck!
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: DO NOT be late to his class. He takes attendance at the very beginning of class (and I mean 8am, not 8:01) and he notes who comes in late, who is not paying attention, etc. He covers all topics for the course very completely, but it is best to come to class having already read the material. He is demanding of your attention, but his class is fun
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--Amazing lectures

comment: Read the textbook, pay attention/participate in class, you'll survive. He has a ton of relevant industry experience. The other reviews are pretty soft,  he is a tougher grader but if you read the textbook and the highlighted learn smarts you can easily get above a 90. The overall grade also if very distributed through different assignments.

Take his class if you are good at multiple choices. Almost no students would get overall hw and presentation scores lower than 87 points. The  biggest issue is the three tests. Extremely hard tests. A hint here: If you have to take his class, after he graded your tests, try to argue with him about questions you got wrong, he make mistake sometimes

I enjoyed Professor Powers class for the most part. He knows what he's talking about & gives good examples. There is hw due every class but its very helpful in learning how to apply the material. Tests are fair & you'll do well if you listen in class & read the textbook. Only complaint is he seemed unnecessarily hard in grading final presentation
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--TEST HEAVY

comment: Not bad. Lectures done well and he has a lot of experience in the field. He is very clear about what he wants for assignments and is very strict about getting that. Exams are a little tricky - but he does let you dispute questionable answers. Again, strict, but gets his point across well.
Worst professor I've ever had. Huge workload for an introductory class. Tests are very hard. Hard to take notes he whizzes through powerpoints and doesn't allow laptops. AVOID
He's actually a really nice guy. He was really understanding and helpful towards me.
avoid at all costs.... test heavy class and hard OVERALL.  AVOOD HIM GUYS!!!!
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment: No practice for tests forever

He is clear about what he teaches. Super interested in his subject. His tests are fair game and not easy to ace if you dont study. Lots of his homework answers can be found online. Participation is important so make sure he knows your name

A bloated, inconsiderate, do-things-strictly-by-his-own-arbitrary-book kind of guy. Has the most inane and draconian attendance rules; if you're late to class even by a minute, you're counted absent all day. He refuses to except late work. He lacks total sympathy, even scoffed when I told him my grandfather was dying. A bureaucratic oaf.

Professor Power is the most rude and disrespectful professor I've ever had the displeasure of "learning" from at Northeastern. He acts like he could care less about how you perform in his class and is not willing to help at all when asked. If you want to save your GPA, don't take this guy.

In-class participation and coming to class is 20% of your grade. His tests are 50 multiple choice questions (averages: 80-84) Not an easy A, you must work for it. Make sure to be as creative as possible whenever you have a presentation. He expects a lot from you. Overall he is a very nice guy but I don't really think he is that good of a professor.

No negotiations, no slack, very strict when it comes to participation and tardiness. Penalized me for missing classes that I didn't miss. Lectures are well-explained and tests are fair, but policies are unforgiving.

Professor power has little to no interest in helping anyone in class. He just zooms through material, tells you only to study his slideshows, then the exams are on book material and anything else he decides. Avoid at all costs.

The worst professor I have ever had at Northeaster. Extremely hard exams and he doesn't make you feel comfortable to participate in class. I regretted taking the transportation class with him. Avoid if you can!

I loved this class. It is VERY hard to get an A in but I felt that I learned a lot. The tests are hard and sometimes the questions misleading. While there are assignments almost every class he makes it fun and class isn't boring.

This professor is extremely disrespectful to students. The tests he writes are grammatically incorrect which makes it difficult to understand the questions that are being asked. He gives little to no feedback for means of improvement. His grading is arbitrary and he provides no basis upon where he makes up his numbers. DO NOT TAKE HIM!
Goes through power points too fast for you to write things down. Tests are very hard and confusing. Direspectful to students. Doesnt provide good feedback. DONT TAKE HIM.
Lectures make material seem super easy, but the tests will get you

Great person, really cares about his students. If you're rude he doesn't tolerate it. He works hard for every student he has and wants to see effort from us. Makes class SOO enjoyable. So much knowledge for the field, and has great connections. Always willing to help students.

The thing people don't like about this prof is that he's very blunt. You can take that to mean a good thing or a bad thing. At the beginning of each year, he lays out everything he's going to do in his syllabus. Make sure you follow that syllabus, and you'll be fine. As long as you're a hard worker, you'll enjoy it. If not, then don't.
He's class is interesting but he is definitely a tough grader. Try take a nap play your phone in class and see what will happen.

Bans computers in the class. Goes through power points too fast for you to write things down. Includes extra material in the powerpoint that he tests on but doesn't leave on the screen long enough for you to write it down. Most of the syllabus is clear, but for the parts that aren't he doesn't see the need for elaboration. No real feedback on cases

Mr Power is crazy when it comes to his guest speakers and attendance. Unfortuantely it seems like he has so many personal issues that he's angry at the students all the time. Extremely uptight and terrorizing that you worry about class more than about learning.

Great man, if you put in effort, he will take notice. AS simple as that. The course material is kept interesting, and participating only helps you. He isn't out to get you and he doesn't play favorites. If this is your major, take this class with him.

I had Power for SC&OM. Studied 10 hours a week (reading the chapter + homework), participated in class, went to office hours.His class itself is interesting, seems simple during the lecture but his tests are SUPER ambigious, very hard to get above a 70%. He won't help you out and will not negotiate grades even when he made a mistake. dont take him!

he knows a great deal and can teach you a lot.  put some effort in and you will probably get a B+...im getting a B a did very little studying.  attendance is a must for him...always be there and never leave early...never use your phone either.  he's funny, too, so class isn't bad.  use the ppt slides for all your projects - they're always available

Supply Chain Management is not hard topic yet somehow he makes it really tough. You get stuff from point A to point B, everything else is extra. If you want to work really hard for a bad grade and take a class from a "professor" who can be nasty and disrespectful then this is the class for you.
He's a good professor, very clear with his ideas. But if you just don't pay attention, he becomes downright nasty. Just pull your phone out and see what happens...
He is a good teacher, but the way his supply chain class is graded, getting an A is very difficult.

One thing to know about this class is that getting an A is no as easy as often thought. That apart, prof. Power is a really good professor with a great sense of humor and is always willing to help. Don't ever use your cellphone or sleep in class (even if it's 8am) or he will become your worst nightmare. All in all a great professor.

He's a true goofball, a real nice guy and a great professor. He is really passionate about the subject and makes the class seem actually quite entertaining. However, don't you EVER sleep, space out or use your cellphone in class. He will crush you down and penalize you quite severely. Course load is fair but meaningful.

Very enthusiastic, difficult grader. Make sure you participate during every class (big part of grade-25%). Do well on the quizzes and final business plan w/presentation (40%). There are definitely easier professors for the subject but he is very comprehensive and helpful.
He is super hard professor! if you wanna an A, never take his class. I got my first B in my life when I had with him. So upset!

Enthusiasm. This is the key. Power is a nice guy, and he's worked hard all his life. Takes the same approach to teaching, and expects you to do the same. Like I said, show enthusiasm and read the chapters, or even just the slides if ur lazy/smart, and you'll get an A and learn a lot. DONT USE UR CELL PHONE!
LOVE POWER! he's amazing! easy grader, easy to follow, great stories, doesn't waste class time and we got out early a lot!
Amazing teacher! Hilarious jokes. and people who say he's mean are just the jerks he's called out

Really helpful guy.  Unlike the rest of the class I really enjoyed the TJX project that takes up most of the class and he really wants to help you with this.  Writing a 35 page business plan might suck but just one semester later I've referred to it 10+ times for help in other classes in terms of formatting and projects.  Funny stories, no final.
Fun class but IMPOSSIBLE to get an A. I am a straight A student and I busted my butt in this class and only got a B+. If you want an A, don't take this professor!

All of these negative comments are true.  Calls anyone out, not understandable of your situation and makes no sense grading.  We had 3 tests; the first one was too easy, second one everyone failed (he had to drop it) and the third one made no sense and got curved.  If you enjoy random stories about FedEx, tough grading and being insulted take this.
Power is a great teacher.  He's very clear, and I learned a lot.  As long as you prepare for the quizzes and work hard on your project, you'll do fine.

Disagree with the previous ratings. If you go to class, pay attention (dont sleep), and give an honest effort he will show you nothing but respect. The material isn't exciting, but Power is a great professor and his lectures are always clear and easy to pay attention to. Only complaint I have is that the test questions are ridiculously specific.

So awful. Do not take this class. Especially if it's for an MIS elective - the guy is a joke, he constantly yells at students like they're children, and knows nothing about current SCM. Should be an easy A, yet was everyone's hardest class. Don't take 201 with this guy!!!

In-class lectures vaguely overlapped with the text book, leaving us VERY unprepared for exams. He could also stand to be nicer to his students, rather than alienating and embarrassing people in front of their peers. Who does that? Not even a middle-school bully struggling with adolescence issues is as mean as Professor Power sometimes was in class.
Really good guy. Quizzes are pretty ridiculously hard but don't count that much. Presentations are most of the grade. Tough grader.

Professor Power is a good guy. In intro. to business you take about 10 quizzes and attendance is mandatory. We also did a group project that made up 50% of our grade. He is completely fair, he is extremely helpful, and if you don't do any work that's the only way you will do poorly. Otherwise, you attend class, study, and ask for help. you'll be fi

Just finished up the semester with this professor...have to say was by far my favorite. Awesome guy, always available to help you out and great at explaining things. We had a lot of work compared to my friends but I learned a ton more than all of them and I really became much more interested in business after this class.

You will have 3 exams that make up most of your grade. His lectures cover a lot of material, but youd fail if you took rigorous notes at each class. You have to go through each studyguide per chapter and answer each T/F,MC,etc. Do that and you will do fine on the exams and in the class. NEVER fall asleep in class. EVER. Don't go if you feel sleepy.

Overall nice guy, hard grader and unclear on what should be put on powerpoints. His comments made me frustrated because he gave you the same grade no matter how hard you worked to improve. Make sure you go to class, do your homework and study for his random and hard quizes.

Very entertaining, but tough to reach by email, not crystal clear about requirements on powerpoints, and is not objective when it comes to grading.  He was very skeptical of our idea for the business project, and our consultant had no idea where some of the comments were coming from on our evaluations, or why we continuously got C's on everything.

He has an extremely short fuse.  He victimizes the students on his bad side and embarrasses them inappropriately in front of the whole class.  He is a control freak and a tough grader.  NOT A NICE PERSON.  That being said, he is very smart, experienced, and knows his stuff.  This is one of those classes that wish you could skip every time.
He gave everyone the same grade on every singe presentation (B).  He's very charasmatic and talks about the same UPS stories all the time

Power is a really nice guy. He loves business and wants you to love it too. He tends to be more strict than the other intro to business teachers, but I also learned way more than my friends in the other classes. The only real work is the business plan and presentations. Go to class and pay attention and you will love him too.
He's such a difficult man to work with. He seemingly just dislikes everyone equally.
This rating has been removed as per our site guidelines.
horible professor. lets his emotions get the best of him. class is useless tought my self everything from the textbook.

Professor Power is a good local guy, who is demanding of good work, but isn't going to kill you with homework or boring lectures, if you just listen to what he says and always attend class you'll be fine
Dont piss him off..haha, aside from that...he's great.. sure kept me awake in class
emotional and intense
Power is a good teacher.  Ethics is a boring subject, but he keeps you interested.  The debates were fun.

I'm taking an International Bus class with him and he doesn't know what he talks about. He's always talking about his SCM job he used to work for. He skips a ton of slides because he doesn't know how to teach them!! He'll show videos. You need to do a presentation. Particpating in class is key. Also know current news. He's an avg teacher.
Bad teacher, this is the first time that a professor miss more class than I do. If you want to learn something, you should avoid this techer.

ok hes an easy teacher, but your not going to get your moneys worth.  he has cancelled 5 classes and usually ends class an hour to an hour and a half early. i pay for my education so i get pissed when teachers do that.  im tqlking to the dean tommorow.
No Comments
Very funny guy, very nice guy, very personal with students. Excellent, experienced, and knowledgable teacher. Very enjoyable.
Lovely teacher!!!!!!!!!!
Awesome teacher.  Tells you exactly whats going to be on the tests.  Lots of work, def. worth it!

In class there is 2 presentations, 1 solo, 1 group, no final test or paper just a group project. Very smart guy with lots of knowledge. Pay attention in class and you will get at least a B. Participation is a must.
Global Supply Chain Management, Do the work (which is easy), pay attention, and show effort. You'll get a good grade and make a great reference with this professor! UPS Tour ~ hahaa
