History, his signature course, difficult because he only lectures; but is great at it; the quizes can be tough, and the final (4 take home questions/4 pages) took me 10 hours! But, he is always available, loves the material and loves teaching.  Absolutely recommend.

I had him for History of Media after our original professor had to drop out for the semester. He integrated us into his history of journalism class and did a great job working with the change. I would reccomend him in a heartbeat, and I'm planning on taking more of his classes in the future. Great guy, great professor!
Chuck is definitely my favorite prof. at this school. I've had him for three classes and he's the bomb.

I had Chuck for Day's News, easy class provided you read the Globe, TMZ, ESPN and WBZ's website for news quizzes. Papers are kinda random but fairly easy. He's very liberally biased and for a JRNL class that showed way too much. Very enthusiastic, brings energy that some professors half his age don't.

Chuck is a great professor. The class is not hard as long as you listen to him in class. You don't even have to read the books, if something is on the test and only in the book he'll tell you. But his tests consist mostly of what he says in lectures. Entertaining, extremely knowledgeable, and only wants you to do well. Best professor at NU yet.

Chuck is a nice guy, but this class is not the best. his lectures can be interesting, but his tests are horrible. only way to do well is to make flash cards of the people in lectures and in the readings and memorize everything they did. papers are not fun, but aren't horrible. the bright side is he is always in his office and is willing to help.

chuck's a smart guy and really knows what he's talking about. class is usually dull, but i've also had some of the most interesting discussions in it. random grader. attendance def mandatory. if youre not lazy and actually interested in the subject, id imagine itd be pretty easy to get an A.
Top two profs I've had at Northeastern. Take history of journalism! its so great!

one of the hardest classes i have ever taken. i studied my ass off and i still managed to do poorly on his tests. you must go to class and you must write down everything he says so you can memorize it for the tests. very cocky, interesting guy, horribly unfair and random grader.

A really fun class. Attendance isn't mandatory, but you're pretty much screwed if you don't show up. In love with his subject, in love with hearing himself talk about it, but really tries to make the class interesting for those who may not find it so fascinating.

he is an awesome guy. could get very vain in lectures, he's very proud of all he's done. classes could be great or horribly boring. you have to study the newspaper daily like it's your life for the new's quizes. overall though, he really cares about journalism and his students though, so he knows what he's talking about.

He does not take attendance but if you do not go to class, you are in for a bad grade. Pay attention and TAKE NOTES. Everything he talks about in class will be on the test. He is really vague with assignments so ask a million questions or get help.

Chuck is a nice guy overall. the classes were hit or miss. Some were really boring and others were really heated discussions. News quizes get obnoxious, you HAVE to read the newspaper and watch the news to pass the class, theres no way around it. He knows a lot about the topic, so you do learn a lot.

Be carefull in this class. To pass, being in class is nearly a must. He covers almost everything in class, barely read the books. Take lots of notes and quote him. He loves to hear himself in the answers of tests. If you dont take good notes and dont have good attention, I would not take this class. Be prepared. He does talk down the students .

Professor Fountain is the reason I was excited about coming to NU. After I heard him speak at Welcome Day I couldn't wait to get here because he's so passionate about journalism and he really knows everything there is to know. He has a rep for being a tough grader but if you go to class and take detailed notes you'll be fine.

Not only does he talk down to his students, but he is threatened by intellect and would rather make you feel as though you're wrong, then correct his own mistakes. His teaching skills are under par and should consider a new career choice. I'm sure under all the condescending remarks, he's an intelligent, caring man.. But teaching is not his calling

Oh wow. Knows his stuff, but is the hardest grader I've ever had. Close to impossible to get A's on tests. Does make class interesting though, I'll give him that. But if you're looking for an easy A, or easy B for that matter, dont take this class.

An amazing teacher, and the best I've had so far at NU! He's very passionate about his subject, and really knows his stuff. He's always been available for help, and really respects his students. I'd recommend anyone- journalism major or not- to take his class.
Ohh Chuck. Very knowledgeable, easily excitable, knows his****. Very particular on tests. Dease class.

History of Journalism Teacher. Knows his stuff and makes the class very interesting, but he is a very hard grader. I have a 3.9 GPA and I am a 90's student. I got a 46 on my first test. You can answer the test questions right, but he wants what he thinks is important, not the real reason.

Chuck Fountain is more enthusiastic than any professor I've had at NU.  The passion he has for the subject and the delivery of his lecturing bring to life the topics being discussed.  He takes his work, as well as his students, very seriously.  He's extremely attentive to students' questions, in and out of the classroom, and he's always available.  Chuck has inspired me to pursue journalism in school and possibly as a career.

A great resource on the history of journalism, he's right at home teaching that class. I wish I remembered half of the things I learned in that class. In my limited experience, not the most personable guy thereafter.

Never a dull moment. Belts out what he wants to say, and I've never caught him saying things he's not an expert about. VERY, and I mean VERY!!!! knowledgable about what he talks about. Even though the class is one big lecture, he makes them the most interesting lectures one could possibly imagine.

Professor Fountain is not only a professor but an advisor for the School of Journalism, therefore he has had a lot of experience with dealing with students and helping them. His class is always interesting and his ways of teaching is amazing. He's very cle
Chuck Fountain is an awesome guy, and he has a totally sweet bow tie.

Oh man, Chuck Fountain. This guy knows his stuff, and is compelling, and is a spit-talker. Absolutely fascinating one-on-one. Sure, he likes the sound of his own voice, but at least he's got plenty of interesting stuff to say.

This man loves to hear himself talk.  Guys will get along great with him, girls not so much.  I don't want to go into print journalism anymore because of him, he killed the desire.  His ego is out of control, I counted down the days I had until no more fountain. If you are taking another journalism class at the time I would avoid him.

He is the man! I had him for HST/JRN and will in the future, but he's immediately a favorite of mine. I didn't use him much outside of class, but he was very accomodating. His HST class, he took what could have been a utterly boring class and made it very engrossing. TAKE HIM! Grades a bit tough.

Chuck is a great guy, once you get on his good side.  Come to class, stay awake and nod attentively when he looks at you.  Go to his office and talk about the 1903 Worlds Series or any deadball era baseball, this type of discussion will serve you well.  His sports writing class is incredible.
Very smart. Very very available for help, and that can't be understated. If you don't like him, it's probably cause he didn't like you.
Total ****.  Likes to hear himself talk.  Doesn't aknowledge students out of class.  Pompous jerk...and boring lectures
awsome
Great professor with a huge amount of knowledge! Is one of those prof who is willing to help you out as much as possible and makes himself available more than any prof. i have had here

You will not find a more knowlegeable, more well versed Journalism teacher at Northeastern.   He genuinly cares about the students, and will help you as much as possible.  The best overall journalism teacher at this school, no doubt about it.

He is a great speaker. He is very full of himself. He could probably spend a whole lecture talking about himself. He knows his journalism though. He knows what he wants in a student, he'll tell you. Do what he says and you'll do well.
He is a horrible teacher. Very boring and loves to talk about himself. I don't recommend taking any classes with him. He is rude and speaks down to almost all students.
Very smart; any journalism show take his history of journalism class if you want to have a clue in this business
A great speaker and he knows what he is talking about. He is haughty but he kept my intention in a class that could have been very boring.

Hated him at first. Can be very full of him self and boring. Also can be quite funny at times. Don't take History of Journalism with him but Sports Writing is good. Meet with him in his office... he likes that.
He knows what he's talking about but doesn't always know how to tell you about it. Super nice personality and I managed to do well in his class. Might have been better in-person.

Professor Smith is one of my favorite professors. His lectures are engaging and he is really knowledgeable about the subjects. He does a great job of not putting his own opinions into discussions. There is a good amount of reading but it is doable if you stay on top of it.

Prof. Smith is a great professor who is clearly very interested in the material. He is a genuinely nice guy and his lectures though long, are not boring. There is a decent amount of written work but the key is to read everything thoroughly and participate in class. If you do that the other assignments should be a breeze.

took Ethics and Politics of work. He is an energetic and entertaining lecturer. He also did a great job of assigning a reasonable amount of reading and writing. Sometimes I got a bit lost since he understands philosophy so well and I do not, but I really liked the class.

Mr. Smith is really high energy (too much for some people I talked to, but I enjoyed it) and class time is entirely devoted to group discussion about the reading. There were only like 5 things in the grade book for me at the end of the semester, but he was really generous with my grade on the midterm and final papers imo.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: amazing teacher. passionate. compassionate. understanding. good teacher if you work hard and show up to class. if not, you'll have a hard time. :)

Smith is the dude! Very funny and keeps a really open and engaging class discussion. Attendance not mandatory but he does NOT like it when people dont show up. Readings are gone over in the lecture, papers are kinda weird but just go to office hours hes super helpful 1on1. Scatterbrained is a good word but hes super excitable and passionate!
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria

comment: Really funny, easy A if you read and talk in class. Takes attendance sometimes. Uses discussion board posts, participation, 2 papers, and 3 assignments for grade.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Clear grading criteria

comment: Matthew Smith is a funny guy and a decent professor. The class is conversation based instead of lecture based which is a good way to approach philosophy. He's a little scatter brained but he was good at making you think. The readings were also interesting for the most part and very diverse, so you get exposed to lots of different ideas.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: Smith's lectures and assignments were unorganized at times, and he was a little conceited. He clearly answered questions, and tried to be objective, but we studied only leftist theories without exploring counter arguments. Very tough grader, but fair. Definitely go to office hours before a paper is due, he is much more approachable one on one.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Professor Lupi was overall a super chill and amazing professor. He did a ton of practice during class and made sure we understood everything before the quizzes/exams. He didn't look at the Zoom chat too much, but he was always clear with his work and expectations.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures

comment: Great class. His lectures are very example-driven, which I personally find helpful. If you feel comfortable doing the problems in lecture / on the homework, then quizzes and exams shouldn't be an issue. Also, he has a great fashion sense

Lupi is a perfect professor for math. He moves quickly but is extremely thorough, and he's always willing to pause and answer questions. I highly recommend attending every class and writing down everything he writes on the board, as each lecture is packed with info. Though he goes quickly and gives lots of information, I never found it unmanageable

I love Professor Lupi! He's great at explaining things and always makes sure students understand the material. If you have a question he'll always answer it fully and thoroughly. He really cares about his students and is really accommodating. He also wears awesome sweaters every class.

Was the best math prof Ive had before COVID19 sent us home. He gives great lectures that are concise and clear. He makes everything set up so his practice problems in class are what you see on quizzes and tests. Often lets us out early. Grade professor (wasnt that helpful for online but in-person hes top-notch)
ratingTags: Graded by few things--Amazing lectures--Lecture heavy

comment: I love professor Lupi! He's a bit quiet and he has to warm up to the class, but he is a really great teacher. When I was stuck on something, he was really patient and helped me through it in office hours. One of the best math teacher's I've ever had.

just like for every other math class, you should do the homework. lupi does his job as a professor (which I guess makes him above average) but I've had plenty of better professors. he's kind of awkward as a person and talking to him is weird. although I did learn in his class, I attribute most of it to the homework, not his lectures.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Lots of homework--Clear grading criteria

comment: Professor Lupi is a very good professor. His lectures are always clear and he moves at a good pace. He is a very fair grader, and his class does not require too much outside work.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Graded by few things--Clear grading criteria

comment: Lupi boils complex math ideas into simple and repetitive math operations. He can answer almost all your questions. His quizzes and homework are very reasonable and they definitely prepare you well for the final. All you need to do to succeed in this class is just to go to classes and do his homework. He is also very accessible outside of class.
Goes too fast, harsh grader. Won't take again.
He teaches good.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Skip class? You won't pass.--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: Lupi is a Mathematical GOD. One of the greatest Professors at Northeastern hands-down, take him and you won't regret it. Succinct, easy to understand, accessible, willing to help and work with you- made Differential Equations easy! Quick grading turnaround also a plus.

Lupi is such a great teacher. I had him over the summer and I loved this class. I definitely could've done better but that was my fault. He made the class really easy and understandable. Just do the homework and you're prepared for the quizzes. He genuinely wants what's best for his students.
ratingTags: Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: Lupi is the man. I took differential equations with McOwen and dropped the class after the first midterm - I was doing so bad. Lupi boils down the material to a level that is easy to understand and grades very fairly. Doing the assigned homework is crucial to success, and quizzes and exams are straightforward if you study.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria

comment: Gives very clear, detailed notes. Can be a bit condescending when people ask questions, but he clearly knows his stuff. Some take off more points than others for the same mistake, but if you bring it to Lupi's attention he's pretty good at clearing it up.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--TEST HEAVY--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Prof. Lupi explains the process of differential equations very clearly. He gives clear step-by-step procedures and all quizes match examples he does in class. However, he doesn't really explain anything conceptually. Not a good choice if you want conceptual understanding, amazing choice if you just want to learn the procedure & material. Easy A.

Very well-versed in the materials and efficient with the notes & class time. Fair testing, and went over proofs satisfyingly. Could have explained the concepts more though- the class was very computational and things were introduced often in a "memorize this" sort of way. Liked his style and honestly wish he talked about himself some more!
ratingTags: Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: My biggest challenge with this class was the fact that there were about 100 students in one class.

Great professor. I wish I could take him again but he only teaches this class. He tells you theory, then examples, then you practice the same stuff for homework, then you already know how to do all the problems on the exams and quizzes. This is how a math class should be: clear and understandable. You have to go to class; just write down everything
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria--Amazing lectures

comment: Lupi is the best prof I've ever had. He explains things very clearly & step by step. He cares about his students, but I can see how some see him as a harsh guy; he's just straight forward but tbh its kind of amusing in class. He's ALWAYS prepared, shows you everything you'll come across on hw, quizzes, & exams. He's known to best for diff equ prof

Lupi is the best math teacher I have ever had. He is clear and concise in his lectures and his examples are the hardest things you'll see beyond the occasional homework problem (that has a video). The weekly quizzes are helpful (and from the hw), and if you do better on the final than one of the midterms, he'll replace the midterm grade.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures--Would take again

comment: Lupi is a solid professor for straight up learning the material. Has very organized lectures, is very efficient with time and sets you up well for the quizzes and tests. Can come across as a little cocky and cruel, but will still help you out if you request it. Doing homework really helps on the tests and quizzes as well, as he will point out.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures--Would take again

comment: Lupi is one of the best professors I've had.  I'm not a math major and DiffEq was one of my favorite classes last semester.  His lectures are fast-paced but very straightforward.  His office hours are a huge help.  Every problem I remember seeing on tests was either an example or in the homework.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Go to the classes, he explains everything you need to know and you don't have to read the textbook as long as you have your notes. His example problems 99% of the time cover all of the types of problems you will ever see, and that 1% is covered by the video solutions to the textbook problems. Nice class, a good break from Calc 3.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Fast pace but as long as you attend class and do homework, there's nothing to worry about. Very straightforward professor
ratingTags: Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: Super helpful and does tons of practice problems in class to really enforce the material. the curriculum itself is a bit fast paced but he does a good job of making sure that you learn it all. The class does require a bit of effort though.

Bob Lupi is an excellent professor. His class is exactly what you want in a math class: straightforward grading expectations, quality lectures and accompanying notes, and help available when you need it. If you make the effort to go to his class it is not hard to nail the quizzes every week and do well on the exams. Highly recommend him!
Fun guy, seems to actually care
He knows how to teach. The quizzes like homework and examples he gave in class. Go to class, you can get an A.
Favorite professor. Favorite class. You can't beat Bob Lupi. Guy knows his stuff. If you come to class, you get an A

Prof Lupi knows how to teach. One of the best math professors I've had to date and he will stop the class to make sure a student understands. If you go to class, you'll understand. He explains it well and the quizzes are like problems he does in class.

Excellent guy, excellent professor. He is clear and concise and willing to explain anything twice in his lecture. The quizzes and exams are on par with the rest of the course, he is a pretty lenient grader. Best math professor I've had at Northeastern.
He could be very abrupt with students. But he knows the material. Textbook used if you miss class or want to do the homework. Much more doable class than Calculus 3.

Im majoring in mech engineering and minoring in math so ive take a lot of math classes. lupi is one of the best math professors ive ever had in my life. concise, clear, freakin smart, freakin easy, excellent at teaching, excellent at explaining, knows his stuff, very helpful and his quizzes are mad easy. very lenient grader. AMAZING PROF.
He's very helpful and flexible. He gives good in class notes. Easy weekly quizzes. Homeworks are optional. A bit overrated tho when it comes to clarity, but I recommend him.
I wish we did more derivations of formulas. But all in all, he was a great teacher. Maybe a little boring if math isn't your thing. Very smart and patient.
Great Teacher. Made subject matter really clear and didnt try to trick you on any quizzes. Always willing to take questions even stupid ones. Definitely want to take a class with him again.
This guy is the man. I wish i had him for all my calc classes. Very clear, knows his stuff, helps you get your grade up if you need. Very clear on what is expected on quizzes and tests.
Best Calc. teacher ever.  The material in calculus 2 is difficult, but Lupi is a great lecturer.

Helpful, knowledgeable, provides a lot of examples, quizzes are kinda tricky, grades leniently, midterm & final are doable, sometimes he makes things complicated on the board, but still overall as a good professor.

Extremely efficient and clear.  Come to class and expect to pay close attention for greatest benefit. Quizzes and classes are both fair and short.  He ends class early for some of the easier stuff, but only if everyone claims that they understand.  He knows he's a good teacher, so don't expect sympathy if you skip class and fail.

Extremely efficient: Gives you a quick run down of the material, does a bunch of examples, quizzes you every week. Great at explaining things; some of the quizzes were a little hard though. Overall great prof., especially if you're not great at calc but need to take it.
Great Professor. One of the best that I have had at Northeastern so far. He makes everything very easy.

He is a very good teacher, although his personality is a little dry. His notes are extremely useful and necessary. He provides plenty of examples to help guide you through the class. Don't skip class or you will fall behind. The class is not easy but his teaching makes it fairly straight forward and doable. Good teacher, would recommend.
By far, without a doubt, the best professor at Northeastern. Makes everything seem so easy.

He enters room. Answers homework questions. Does new examples. Allows class to try new examples. Assigns homework. Lets everyone out early if it was clear to everyone. Bang bang bang, super-clear, very effective.  Best math teacher possible.

I took calc 3 with him... He is very reasonable and patient... Just attend his classes and ul be fine... One of the better Math teachers... Quizzes are similar to homework assignments and if u think ur unfairly graded speak to him and he give u a good explanation or give u more partial credit...
Excellent professor. He always provides clear example of the subjects.

an AMAZING teacher! Best math teacher in the dept that i've found so far. organized, fast paced, easy to understand, outlines the subject, and basically awesome. homework collected, weekly quizzes, 1 midterm + 1 final. VERY HELPFUL! TAKE THIS CLASS!
Very fast paced and extremely informational.  Everything is broken down and organized in a fashion that is easy to learn a difficult subject.  Nice & helpful.

This teacher explains math in the most simple way possible, and is always willing to answer your questions. However due to his complete and total lack of personality, if you ask a stupid question he will make you feel like a stupid person. Tests and quizzes are difficult, but should be no problem if you do the homework and listen to him in class
No Comments
Lupi is awesome! Lots of notes, but they help a bunch. Not a lot of homework, not strict either. Easy quizes because they're basically all hw problems. Tests are tough but fair. Fair grader, too.

Lupi seems kinda austere, but he knows his stuff, and if you take good notes and pay attention, you'll know it too.  Helpful with homework, and fairly so at office hours, but know exactly why you're going before you do.  A no-bull teacher, and a fairly easy A.
One of the best. Can take difficult material and make it bearable. Pleasant, helpful, and clearly wants his students to learn. Register early, his classes fill up quickly.

Excellent calc teacher. very enthusiastic about teaching. examples are very good and help with the weekly quizzes. if you do the homework assignments its easy to get a 100 on every quiz. the midterms and final were reasonable too.
very nice, very helpful, tends to talk quite fast while giving a lot of notes
Great teacher, makes me actually go to class.

Explains mathematical concepts very well and his expectations are clear.  I never once had to turn to the book to learn the material; he taught all the important things in class.  If you pay attention and do the homework you'll be fine.
Extremely helpful and always very fair with quizzes and tests; homework optional only counted towards if a grade is borderline; highly reccomended as a professor

LUPI IS THE MAN - he explains everything really well and is very helpful in aiding people who don't understand the material. If you do the work, the class isn't very hard and there's never a lot of work. RECCOMENDED
Not much personality to this one, but he's a good, clear, fair teacher. If you do the homework and aren't retarded you should get the stuff no problem.
not bad teacher but avoid if possible

I would never recommend this professor. Honestly the worst professor ever. The content isn't difficult, but it's hard to get an A in his class. Every assignment is a presentation, which takes almost the whole class and he doesn't really teach. Never give any feedback so you don't know where you lose points. It takes weeks for him to give a grade.
ratingTags: Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.--Group projects

comment: Never grades any assignments and assigns many papers. He wanted us to learn from what we did wrong in our papers but wouldn't grade our papers. When we asked him to grade them so we could learn from our mistakes he said no. Extremely vague and repetitive information, felt like we were learning the same few things over and over again.
ratingTags: Graded by few things--Group projects--So many papers

comment: Great teacher, he expects a lot from you, but you get a lot out of the course.

comment: Does not post grades or feedbacks of your midterm, homework, and presentations before the final Does not provide informing insight Let you do the case study all by yourselves presentation everyday, heavy workload Does not care about students, does not want to spend time with students to solve problems after class

Wastes in-class time talking about current events. Expects you to do the slides and read the book yourself. You're better off with another professor.  Says class participation is everything, but doesn't remember much.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Get ready to read--Participation matters

comment: The most boring class I took at NEU. His lets the students take the tests online but the material was completely different from what he taught. Presentations every class. Participation matters but he doesn't seem to have good memory. Do no recommend.

Just a mere $5000 Project Management class to add a bullet to your resume,Professor just survives by boasting about his contracts who live in 19th century thought process. If you are innovative or a person who thinks out of the box for project management approach , please avoid it, Simply a useless knuckle head.

Not the best professor I had, to sum it up, you will have to do tons of unnecessary work. The homework for me averaged from 50 to 70 problems a week. Combined with poorly explained material, this makes the subject very difficult, as half of the problems are not explained in class. The tests are also very hard, so my advice: pick another professor

Aliska genuinely wants you to learn. She takes your best quiz scores, and drops the rest, with ample room for extra credit. She also has an excellent sense of humor and writes on her iPad, which makes reading her notes super helpful. Everything is very digital, which makes things painless, and the practices closely resemble the real deal for exams.
Best summed up in one word: Yikes.

The single worst professor I have ever had. She doesn't know how to explain anything, and fails to engage with her students at all. She gives out an unnecessary amount of classwork and homework, half of which the material she doesn't go over in class. DO NOT TAKE HER CLASS IF YOU HAVE THE CHOICE!

Worst professor I've ever had. She puts questions on the quizzes and tests that are WAY harder and longer than the homework problems, and she doesn't even respond to emails. She has no energy and always sounds like she doesn't wanna be there when she's giving lectures. Doesn't give a lot of partial credit or feedback either.

Worst teacher you can have. If these reviews aren't enough she is the same Aliska Gibbins that comes up for Florida Institute of Technology and got away by making a second account. Take ANY OTHER professor. She does not care about her students and made my life a living hell while in her class. She does not respond to emails either. I can counite...

The professor is decent. She teaches clearly and follows the syllabus. She is really good at preparing students for exams (she makes practice tests & questions). Sometimes she doesn't explain fully. I would recommend her if you have taken calculus before/are good at calculus. She teaches mostly by showing lots of examples.

Gibbins was the worst teacher that I've ever had. Her lectures consisted of doing problems on the board using new material without explanations. She expected you to learn on your own but the textbook provided was not helpful. She is a very tough grader and partial credit is almost non existant. Absolutely would not take again.

Great professor. Clear about the syllabus and what is necessary to know for the tests. Posts all her notes online. Really good about leaving time for students to ask questions and explaining when students don't understand. Available outside of class. She is great at preparing us for tests and making sure we all get good grades. Highly recommend.

Zero clarity in what we were doing and on how to solve problems. She just sat in her wheelchair on her iPad, at least her dog was cute. She did give credit for hw but the tests were roughhh. Avoid at all costs especially if you didn't take BC calc in high school.

Its never clear what you're supposed to be learning. Just teach yourself everything from the textbook and the internet and use class for examples and practice. She never explains what shes doing in class. Its an easy grade if you know what you're doing but if you're learning the info for the first time its very hard to actually learn anything.

Really solid professor for economics and was helpful and cares for students in office hours and especially when contacted through email about specifics. Your whole grade basically resides on how well you can do on the quizzes but as long as you take notes on his review day lecture then I think the quizzes become much easier to perform well on.

Carlos is a really nice guy who cares about teaching econ. Will spend plenty of time explaining stuff if you're confused. Office hours helped. Tests were hard but very similar to the homework so make sure you know how to do it. Textbook was helpful in addition to lectures but not necessary. Overall liked the class and he's so nice!

I am currently taking Game Theory and Information Economics with Professor Dominguez and felt compelled to leave this review because he is an absolute beast at making inaccessible and overwhelmingly formal material easy to understand and apply. That being said, GO TO CLASS and ask questions - This class is one of the most difficult ECON electives.

Took down all notes in the class, but didn't have to use it once, so don't write notes if you don't want to. There are lecture notes (free) to replace the textbook ($100+). He's open to office hours, sort of helpful. Don't ask too many questions. I was 1-2 points away from a B+. He likes to help the smart kids, but kids like me don't get much help.

One of the best I've experienced. He makes an effort to explain concepts in a lucid manner and makes sure that the class understands.
